url_title: Degenerate Art - 1993, The Nazis vs. Expressionism
url_description: This is a documentary from 1993 by David Grubin (written, produced, and directed) about the art exhibit under the Nazi regime of what they considered to be the most corrupting and corrosive examples of what they called 'Entartete Kunst' or 'Degenerate Art.' The exhibit, which opened in July of 1937, was meant to be laughed at and despised. I ran across it in a class on Modernism and Post-Modernism. The film is not generally available at the time of this writing (other than on VHS). Personally, I could think of no better backdrop for the ideas and pathos of expressionist art than Nazi Germany, shown by a great deal of actual footage (most provided by the Los Angeles County Museum of Art -- they had an exhibit of their own based on the event that same year). The music is similarly striking, including Schoenberg, Hindemith, and Wagner. All of the art shown, by the way, is referenced by name in the end credits, which I include.

On November 11th, most of the world celebrates the end of the First World War. In former Austria-Hungary, it's not too much of a thing (after all, it's a war we started), but we have a better tradition; a goose feast. It originated in the Roman Empire where it was celebrated as the end of the harvest period and two of the most significant traditions are eating goose (associated with Mars, the Roman god of war, it was nicknamed "Avis Martis") and drinking new wine. How to prepare it: 1. Get some goose breast, it has a better calorie-to-protein ratio (pretty much on par with chicken) and doesn't need as much time to roast as a whole goose. 2. Crush some pink peppercorn and salt in a mortar or grinder, sprinkle the goose with it and then pour some red wine over it. I used Blaufr√§nkisch wine, which comes from Hungary. 3. Cover with aluminium foil and roast for 70 minutes. Then remove the foil and roast for 20 more.

cleaned_message: Now to the Soul Cakes recipe, which will suffice for 7 small cakes. Get 40 grams of butter (I used my salted butter) and 40 grams of powdered milk and mix them together to create a paste. Then add a small egg yolk. Sift 110 grams of whole-grain flour into a bowl. Add allspice, ginger, cinnamon and nutmeg and mix well. Combine the dry ingredients with the wet paste and mix. At this point, the dough will most likely be dry and crumbly. Warm 50 ml of milk, add 10 grams of honey and mix. Pour it into the dough. Add 15 grams of raisins (you can cut them in halves or quarters) and knead until you create one piece of dough. Roll the dough out and cut out circles or whatever shapes you prefer. Preheat your oven to 175 C or 350 F and bake the cakes for 15 minutes. Then take them out, flip them and bake for 5 more minutes so that they're equally crunchy from both sides but still slightly soft in the centre. The 7 cakes have 997 calories and 31 grams of protein, which is not bad at all for a dessert. To balance the macro, you can whip some curd cheese with a teaspoon of honey or some spices and eat it with the cakes. As for the taste, they taste completely natural and have a nice smell of wholegrain flour and hints of spices (this time I played it safe with the spices, the next time I'll use more). The recipe seems pretty versatile, you can easily make them with other fruits, cocoa, nuts, etc. But even this basic version is something I'd gladly buy from a bakery.

Since almost 2/3 of you seem to bake, here's the result of my first baking experiment, for which I chose "Soul Cakes" - a simple recipe from medieval England and Ireland. My goal was to test whether sugar could be replaced with powdered milk (although given their origin, it's safe to assume they were originally made without sugar anyway). The answer is simple; yes. 100 grams of semi-skimmed powdered milk contain 430 calories and 31 grams of protein, so the macro ratios are the same as in milk, only 10x concentrated. Therefore it's not only better than sugar but also better than flour. The milk has 45% "sugar" content, however, the sugar we're talking about here is lactose, which is a disaccharide consisting of galactose and glucose. It does not contain any fructose, which means there's no risk of developing a fatty liver. Lactose is about 30% as sweet as sucrose (table sugar) and has about 10 points lower glycemic index.

AND YET To truly live is to have a will, an identity, a thumos that demands more than the slavery the world offers. Slavery in the ancient world wasn‚Äôt considered a sin by the enslavers ‚Äì it was held against the slaves themselves, who lacked the dignity to risk or take their own lives rather than be the tool of someone else. Today, we are faced with the same choice. We must fight to prove we are free. It‚Äôs tempting to just stay in cover and never emerge, to take what they‚Äôve given us. Yet the truth is they have left nothing for us. It seems hopeless. So why then is there this flame in the darkness? Why is there a flag, torn and covered with blood, being raised above the mud? People are terrified. They have little and are scared of losing more. And yet, people keep finding their way to the banner of strength. They cut off our communications. They steal our money. They promise to expel us from society. And yet, operatives still gather ‚Äì at this moment ‚Äì around fires throughout the world. They use their lackeys to publish lies and libels against us. They use their greatest strength, their utter domination of media, to try to define who we are and what we are. And yet, people throw it off, looking past what they have been told, claiming their own identity and making their own judgement. Their most dedicated slaves directly threaten us with harm or death. They send their insults, boasting that they will spill our blood and sack our holy places. And yet, when the moment comes, they are nowhere to be found, and the only fires that rise are our own. The endless war saps the time, energy, and spirit of the strongest souls. Families don‚Äôt understand. Friends don‚Äôt want to get involved. Women grow jealous of something that takes away attention. And yet, at every event, at every retreat, at every ritual, men travel hundreds of miles or cross oceans to be with people they have never met to experience something they don‚Äôt yet understand, and walk away forever changed. The world tells us that it is perverse to seek strength, competition, and struggle. It tells these ideas are outdated, and we need to ‚Äúreimagine‚Äù masculinity itself for our own benefit. And yet, it‚Äôs only after conflict and competition, when men spill blood fighting against each other and then embrace afterward, that we get some small glimpse of what friendship could be. The screens offer us virtual adventures, virtual sex, virtual missions, virtual meaning. The dopamine hit makes it difficult to tear away from the tempting, passive consumption. And yet, people do rip themselves away, and instead seek real adventure, real danger, and real brotherhood in tests of body, soul, and spirit. Faith once had the power to shatter kingdoms and move men to surpass their fear of death itself. The sense of ecstasy, of something beyond mere life, of something that is truly separated from the mundane has been altogether lost. Worse, those trusted to safeguard such traditions seem uninterested in them, instead eager to search for relevance from those who despise them. And yet, men seek the new temples in the forests, those eternal things that lie behind the veil of blood and fire. The oaths spoken at ritual have a greater meaning than any written words. Most of all, the world tells us that you must not leave the path that is set out for you. If you associate with this person, read these things, watch this video, use this symbol, go to this place, attend this meeting, wear this clothing ‚Äì you are finished. The supposed promises of the ‚ÄúOpen Society‚Äù disappear overnight with the most powerful people in the world desperately seeking to control what people can say, read, see, and think. The law offers no protection. The costs of disobedience are real and terrifying. Some of the men who speak the boldest are the quickest to fold when the struggle ceases to be a game. And yet, countless people overcome it all, turn their back on those demanding they debase themselves, and put loyalty above all‚Ä¶‚Äù

I want an InBody scan. I walk to a gym without booking, get tested within 15 minutes, instantly get the test results printed on a paper and e-mailed to my mailbox within a few minutes. Costs 15 EUR. I want a DEXA scan. I contact a clinic, they tell me the first available date is in five months. I make a booking, get tested. The nurse tells me they will send me the results by post (what year is it again?). After four weeks of waiting, I e-mail the clinic and ask where my results are. They send me a secure download link with the results of a bone density test. Followed by an e-mail from the doctor, that they performed a wrong kind of test and I should come back to get tested again. Costs 60 EUR. And people wonder why I don't have a GP or a medical record... (But at least I know that my bone density is 118% of the average value for my age.) Also, take into consideration that I came to the clinic voluntarily, healthy and with a specific request of what kind of test I wanted and what for. Imagine what level of service one can receive if he's brought there unconscious by an ambulance with nobody knowing what's wrong with him.

Another lesson from today: Some of you may know that I like South American food. Despite usually eating local food, I found a restaurant here (Zagreb, Croatia) that makes arepas. I decided to give them a try, since the only time I had them was in Washington DC. I look at the list of sides and I see yucas fritas. I like yucas l, but I also see a big nasty deep frier next to the grill and I don‚Äôt like the look of it. I ask: ‚ÄúWhat do you fry the yucas in?‚Äù Staff: ‚ÄúIn oil. Do you want them too?‚Äù Me: ‚ÄúNo, I don‚Äôt eat anything that‚Äôs fried in oil, I‚Äôll just have the arepa.‚Äù The I think for a moment and ask: ‚ÄúI have one more question about the yucas‚Ä¶ could you just dry grill them?‚Äù She: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know, I‚Äôve never tried it, I don‚Äôt know how they‚Äôre going to taste. I can try one and let you taste it. But they‚Äôre already cooked, we just fry them for a short while.‚Äù I ate cooked yucas before, they‚Äôre kind of like overcooked potatoes but totally edible so I say: ‚ÄúOK, you can grill them all, I‚Äôll get them.‚Äù She tells her cook (who looks like she‚Äôs actually from Venezuela or some similar country) to grill them. She then brings them to me. ‚ÄúAre they good? Because I really don‚Äôt know‚Ä¶‚Äù Me: ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre certainly better than fried in oil. I eat food fried in lard, tallow, butter, but not in oil.‚Äù After a short while she comes again: ‚ÄúDo you want a free vegetable salad with them? We‚Äôre closing soon and you look like you eat healthy so I think a salad can be a good idea.‚Äù The lesson: If you do not take your standards seriously, nobody else will. But if you develop a ‚ÄúMy way or no way‚Äù mindset, people, even if they just about understand what you‚Äôre asking them to do, will often come to the conclusion that if you look like you know what you want and look like you‚Äôre determined to get it, they may as well respect you and give it to you.

About quality vs. quantity or what makes a meal special. After witnessing a good few people drinking Coca Cola, talking about eating a cake or heading to the nearest restaurant straight after the bodybuilding competition, I will use this opportunity to talk about the differences between social classes and cultures when it comes to food, celebrations, and treats. If you interact or at least observe people from different social classes celebrate something, it is easy to notice one pattern. Those at the bottom of the social ladder will be happy with pretty much anything, as long as they get a lot of it. The upper classes, on the other hand, are much more focused on quality rather than quantity; think about bringing one bottle of champagne to a party rather than a 12-pack of beers. This has historical reasons. In the past (especially in feudal societies), the peasants often had to deal with shortages of pretty much everything, including food. They had to plan their consumption to make sure they‚Äôd survive the winter and therefore anytime they could eat as much as they wanted, it alone was a reason to celebrate. The nobility, on the other hand, did not have to deal with this. The peasants worked on their fields, they owned forests in which they could hunt and always had access to more food they could realistically eat. Therefore, getting more of the same thing did not impress them. What difference does it make, whether you eat one deer steak or two, if the second one tastes exactly the same as the first one and there‚Äôs 500 more deer living on your land? The nobility understood one thing: Common food does not become special just because there‚Äôs more of it on the plate. (Fun fact: European nobility for this reason tended to disdain vegetables, seeing them as peasants‚Äô food). On the other hand, even for the kings, traveling was slow and often dangerous. Therefore, if a king wanted to impress his court, his best bet was getting something rare from a faraway region that most people in his country have probable never even heard of. Think exotic spices like peppercorns, cinnamon, vanilla but also southern fruits or nuts like grapes, figs, or almonds for those living in the north. And since people from different social classes don‚Äôt tend to mix that much, those habits have not really changed even in the modern times ‚Äì you can see that especially in restaurants where the upper-class ones focus much more on the quality of their ingredients, creative and unique combinations or the visual presentation of the food rather than on filling your plate and subsequently your stomach. (Have you ever seen a Michelin star all-you-can-eat restaurant, a bottomless glass of champagne or people drinking single malt whisky from a bucket?) Think about this the next time you‚Äôre choosing a treat for yourself and treat yourself like a lord, not like a peasant.

‚ÄúThe more you‚Äôre obsessed by something, the better chance you have of achieving it.‚Äù - Frank Zane ‚Äì Today I went for an InBody body composition analysis for the first time since early January (I don‚Äôt go for these too often). The result: 5.5 % body fat*, 182 cm / 6 ft height, 85.7 kg / 189 lbs weight and 79 cm / 31‚Äù waist size. *I got measured twice, the lower result was 5.2%, the higher was 5.7%. In other words, I have gained muscle mass as well as lost body fat. Since my last measurement, which was 8.6%, I attended 5 BJJ competitions, 1 bench press competition, 3 bodybuilding competitions, improved my squat PR to 204 kg / 450 lbs, managed to deadlift 500 lbs, overhead press 100% of my body weight and complete a 100km / 62m bike ride. There are two reasons why I‚Äôm sharing this: 1. The difference between ‚Äúgood‚Äù and ‚Äúgreat‚Äù is in the mindset. The key to continuous growth and progress towards greatness is doing the best you are capable of, not the worst you can get away with. Yes, you can have one cheat meal, yes, you can skip one workout, yes you can party for one night‚Ä¶ but just because you can doesn‚Äôt mean you should. The question shouldn‚Äôt be ‚ÄúCan I?‚Äô, the question should be ‚ÄúWhy would I?‚Äù Would one McDonald‚Äôs menu make me fat? Who gives a fuck, what difference does it make? I couldn‚Äôt care less. I don‚Äôt ask myself ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the worst thing I can eat without getting fat?‚Äù I ask myself ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the best thing I can eat?‚Äù I don‚Äôt know how long you have been following this channel, but my diet is better than it was a year ago. And a year ago it was better than it was two years ago. And in a year from now it will be better than it is today. Why? Why not? The reason why most people will never become better than above average is because they are too attached to their old self. They want to be a new person, but they don‚Äôt want to stop being the old one. Buy you can‚Äôt be both, so you must decide, which one you want to be more. And once you have decided to walk the path towards your new self, when the old you is dragging you back, instead of pulling it with you, you should turn around, shoot him in the head and let him lie there like the useless burden it was to you. Fuck your cheat meal, fuck your occasional treat, fuck your 80/20 rule and all other nonsense. Ad Altiora Tendo. 2. Most people have not only more fat than they think but what‚Äôs more important, more fat than they need. Before I started preparing for bodybuilding competitions, I imagined that when you‚Äôre around 5% body fat (that‚Äôs if you even get there without inhuman doses of gear), you‚Äôre barely alive, feel like shit and can‚Äôt wait for it to end. Guess what? I feel great and I have zero desire to gain any of that fat back. It makes me think of a great quote I heard in Ulfheim / Devotion back in March 2023; ‚ÄúCalories determine how big your body is. Macronutrients determine how it looks. Micronutrients determine how it works.‚Äù When your last meal before stepping on the stage is a bag of Haribo bears and a can of Coca-Cola and the moment you leave the stage you‚Äôre heading straight out to have a cigarette, chances are that if you feel like shit on your competition day, it‚Äôs not because of lack of fat. Sure, you do need some fat to function properly‚Ä¶ but some doesn‚Äôt mean 20 %, when you‚Äôre on a diet and feel like shit, it‚Äôs probably nutrients you‚Äôre missing, not body fat. And even if your goal is to get bigger, it does not mean the best way to do it is by eating garbage (as a matter of fact, I eat the same foods regardless of whether I want to gain or lose weight). STUDY & SCIENCE ‚ÄúYou have not studied nutrition and I have; therefore, you are not an expert and I am!‚Äù I am sure many of us have heard this one before. I certainly have. How true is this statement though? Study (noun): ‚Äúapplication of the mental faculties to the acquisition of knowledge‚Äù. Study (verb): ‚Äúto apply oneself to the acquisition of knowledge, as by reading, investigation, or practice‚Äù. Science (noun): ‚Äúthe systematic study of the structure and behaviour of the physical and natural world through observation, experimentation, and the testing of theories against the evidence obtained‚Äù. When you look at these definitions, you may notice one thing: there is no mention of schools in them. ‚ÄúStudying‚Äù is not a synonym of ‚Äúbeing a student‚Äù. Nowhere do these definitions state, that you can only study something at school. When you read a sentence that says, ‚ÄúLeonardo da Vinci studied the flight of birds and tried to make a flying machine based on his discoveries‚Äù, it does not mean that he studied ornithology, aerodynamics or aerospace engineering. As a matter of fact, Leonardo da Vinci never attended a formal university and therefore did not have any formal education or degree. However, people do not seem to care that his designs and inventions have never been peer-reviewed by scholars or graded by professors. So why does it matter whether your meal plan has been? Anyone can study anything. An illiterate gardener can study the ideal placement of plants in his garden. So yes, if you have spent the past 6+ years writing down all your food, weighing and measuring yourself every morning and observing what happens to your body if you eat this or not eat that, you can absolutely say that you have studied (your own) nutrition. To put it in a perspective; 6 years is what it takes in my country to study medicine and get a M.D. degree. Becoming an officially certified nutrition consultant is a matter of passing a two-week course. One 5-3-1 lifting cycle takes twice as long. Which makes me go even one step further to say that most of those consultants, coaches and experts have not studied shit, because no matter what you read about food, nutrition or health, two weeks simply do not give you enough time for any experimentation or testing to verify whether what you have learned actually works in real world. All you can do in so little time and all it takes to get a certificate is to read and memorise a few pages of text and then repeat it to someone who will give you a piece of paper in return. And let‚Äôs not pretend that it takes much more than that to get a degree from a college or a university, since most academic institutions reward memorization and repetition more than anything else. Think about it this way; if your professor has written his own study on a subject, would he prefer you to quote it to improve his citation index, h-index or impact factor, or to oppose him and say that his study is a pile of nonsense that doesn‚Äôt work and that as someone who cannot bench one plate, he shouldn‚Äôt even be publishing anything on that subject in the first place? Let that sink in and you may realise that the academia is often just one massive circle jerk of people interested more in their own reputation and fame than in anything that would meet the definitions of study or science from the beginning of this text.

Another important point that I want to clarify after reading some of the comments: ANY OIL CAN BE CHEMICALLY REFINED Including olive oil, coconut oil, avocado oil, etc. - they mostly do it to remove any solid particles as well as neutralise its flavour (if you ever tasted an unfiltered olive oil especially now after the harvest season, you know what I‚Äôm talking about). So do not assume that if you buy some cheap olive oil in a supermarket that costs $5 a gallon that you‚Äôre consuming something healthy and beneficial.

A clarification / reminder of what seed oils are: There are two ways you can extract oil from seeds: 1. You crush and press them until you squeeze the oil out. This is the cleaner, more natural but also more laborious and less cost efficient method since some of the oil remains in the crushed seeds. 2. You dissolve the seeds in a blend of chemicals, eliminate the solids either by filtration or by a chemical reaction and what remains is your seed oil. This is much cheaper, however, some of the chemicals used are toxic and the chemical reactions heat the oil to the point where it starts oxidizing. Pumpkin seed oil is a regional delicacy in Austria and surrounding countries. It‚Äôs only used in cold foods such as salads and is pretty much always cold-pressed by the farmers who grow the pumpkins, therefore you can assume it‚Äôs safe to eat. Now; can you get cold-pressed sunflower, canola, peanut, etc. oil? Absolutely; you can as well buy a bag of sunflower seeds and make it at home. However, that‚Äôs not how most of it is produced. Yes, you can find and buy cold-pressed oils from pretty much any seeds you want, but they will be much more expensive than their mass-produced counterparts and as a general rule, don‚Äôt expect to find them in restaurants or pre-packaged foods.

Fun fact: There is a proposed eating ‚Äúdisorder‚Äù named ‚ÄúOrthorexia‚Äù, characterized by an ‚Äúexcessive‚Äù (whatever that‚Äôs supposed to mean in this context) preoccupation with eating healthy food. Its symptoms are supposed to be ‚Äúobsessive focus on food choice, planning, purchase, preparation, and consumption; food regarded primarily as source of health rather than pleasure‚Äù. Which to me sounds like an almost perfect example of order rather than disorder, given the definitions I quoted above, but if you can think of any reasons why planning and being prepared is bad for you, go ahead and let me know in the comments/chat. Until then, I will consider it a proof that our society has become so sick, that it does not hesitate to take a word and twist it so much that it completely reverses its original meaning. By the way, the term ‚ÄúOrthorexia‚Äù (which literally means ‚Äúcorrect diet‚Äù) was first introduced in 1997 by American physician Steven Bratman, M.D. This is his photograph. Every. Single. Time.

Eating disorders. I want to address a subject I am normally not too interested in, but I often come across when discussing nutrition; eating disorders. What is a disorder? Well; it‚Äôs the opposite of order, obviously. The Oxford dictionary defines order as an ‚Äúarrangement‚Äù or a ‚Äúcontrolled state‚Äù. Disorder, as its antonym, is then defined as ‚Äúan untidy state; a lack of order or organization‚Äù. In medical context, it defines it as ‚Äúa condition or illness that causes problems with the way part of the body or brain works‚Äù. As a verb, ‚Äúto order‚Äù can mean ‚Äúto organize / arrange‚Äù but also ‚Äúto give instructions from a position of authority‚Äù. What does an eating disorder look like then? When you put the above together, you can conclude that eating disorder is a disorganized diet, especially one that creates problems with your body. When you cannot achieve your fitness goals (or even live a healthy life) because you either don‚Äôt know or don‚Äôt care what you eat, that‚Äôs a state of disorder. The most prevalent eating disorder is obesity. Now you may say: ‚ÄúBut obesity is not considered an eating disorder!‚Äù Well‚Ä¶ according to whom? According to various English dictionaries, it obviously is. It is not listed in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-5) issued by the American Psychiatric Association (I will use this example, since I assume most of you being from America), but who cares, really? DSM-5 is a document that was created by people and can be changed by people anytime they decide to change it. There are many examples of diagnoses that were either added to it or removed from it. And do not forget that nearly every second doctor is overweight or obese, so you can hardly expect them to objectively diagnose themselves (according to one survey conducted in Britain, 90% of overweight people don‚Äôt even recognize or admit they have a weight problem, let alone are willing to do something about it). The solution is creating order. Organizing your diet from a position of your authority over self. Giving yourself orders and following them. Recognizing a hierarchy to be able to say ‚ÄúThis food is better than that food. I should eat more of this and less of that.‚Äù If you‚Äôre struggling with that, try to find some guidance on this channel or in the related chat group. Alternatively, you can contact me for 1:1 coaching.

‚ÄúMagiun de Prune Topoloveni Il is the best fruit product in the world in 2023. Magiun de Prune Topoloveni is a concentrated spread with a shiny surface made in the town of Topoloveni and the surrounding villages, from local, fully ripe, top-quality dark plums which are boiled over for a long time during the concentration phase. The plums contain high amounts of carbohydrates, natural sugar, and vitamin C because of their ripeness. The only ingredient in the product is the plum, and although it may seem that the plum skins are missing from the jam, they are incorporated into it in order not to lose precious nutrients, fibre and vitamins.‚Äù Why am I sharing this? Because in many western countries, not only it is next to impossible to buy unsweetened fruit jams/marmelades/spreads (unless you live in a major city or shop online) but the producers will also often try to convince you that the sugar has to be used because otherwise their product wouldn‚Äôt be good enough. Well; it wasn‚Äôt used here and the result is the best fruit product in the world. Remember this the next time some greedy merchant tries to sell you jam with sugar - he‚Äôs probably trying to cover the taste of fruits that were either not ripe yet or already rotting. Or simply because sugar is cheaper than fruit.

Himalayan Salt üßÇ üáµüá∞ I want to clarify some facts about Himalayan salt and other non-standard salts, since I often see people who keep making and believing claims that are misleading at best and completely made-up at worst. Himalayan salt is a rock* salt mined in Himalayas, mostly in Pakistan. *I have witnessed people mentioning ‚ÄúHimalayan Sea Salt‚Äù - there‚Äôs no such thing as Himalayan Sea Salt and if anyone doesn‚Äôt knows the difference between sea and rock salt, just ignore whatever they say about food. Now to the main point: Himalayan salt is a salt that contains traces of many other minerals. The key word is: traces. Himalayan salt is still some 95% to 98% sodium chloride (NaCl) with all the other minerals combined adding up to the remaining 2% to 5%. The most dominant of those is potassium. However. Since an adult man needs about 3 grams of potassium a day, you would have to eat more than one pound of Himalayan salt a day. And nobody eats a pound of salt a day and if you did, you would regret it as possibly the most retarded idea you got. By the way, to put things in a perspective; the amount of potassium in Himalayan salt is not much higher than the amount of potassium in a banana. The only difference is, that eating a pound of bananas will not turn all your internal organs into cured meat. And the same applies to all other minerals present in this salt, including minerals such as arsenic, lead or uranium; they are present in clinically insignificant quantities that will neither harm you nor improve your health. Now don‚Äôt get me wrong, I am not saying that Himalayan salt has no place in your kitchen, however, you should treat it as what it is and what chefs use it as; a decorative finishing salt, not a multimineral supplement. Bonus fact: In Pakistan, you can buy a 10lb bag of their local pink salt for about $5. Given its price in the West, I dare say this salt must be their second most profitable export commodity after heroin.

Quite the opposite, my cookbook now contains over 100 recipes you can choose from, comes as a PDF file you can print at home if you want to and costs $15. So much for healthy food being (more) expensive...

DECEMBER CHARGE SUMMARY: For the past four weeks or since coming back from Slovenia on Monday, I ate the following foods: MEAT: chicken, beef, pork, cod, salmon, canned tuna, deli ham. EGGS DAIRY: cottage cheese, curd cheese, white yoghurt, milk, hard cheese for grating CARBS: bread, flour, pasta, potatoes, wheat, rice FATS: olive oil, butter, walnuts, poppy seeds FRUIT: apples, pears, lemons VEGETABLES: onion, celery, celeriac, parsley root, carrot, turnip, cabbage, sauerkraut, canned tomatoes FLAVOURINGS: salt, honey DRINKS: water, green tea, coffee On average, I ate some 2500 calories a day, a minimum of 200 grams of protein, six eggs, 10-20 grams of olive oil, green tea with lemon and raw honey. My food for these 4 weeks cost me $400 / ‚Ç¨365. I spent the most money on eggs, followed by meat, dairy and bread. I did not consume any added sugar, any alcohol and any food not made by myself. I have lost 4.5 lbs and my waist is 0.8‚Äù smaller than it was 4 weeks ago. If you were following my updates for the past four weeks, I hope you have found something inspiring that will put you in a good starting position for 2024.

I am keeping my diet simple this month so I decided to make a really basic dessert from Ukraine. It is called Kutia and it is similar to rice pudding, only made with wheat. The ingredients are wheat, milk, poppy seeds, walnuts, dried pears (or other fruit) and honey. I bought the wheat from a shop and the milk from a farmers market, everything else has been obtained from people's private gardens through my parents or grandparents. Preparation: Soak the wheat in water overnight, then discard the water and cook in milk (use about 1.5 parts of milk for 1 part of wheat) until soft. In the meantime, soak the poppy seeds and the dried fruit (separately) in hot water for at least 30 minutes. Grind the poppy seeds (I used a mortar that I use for my spices). Once the wheat is cooked, add some honey to the milk and mix. Add poppy seeds and dried fruit. Finally, chop and roast some walnuts in a pan and add them to finalise the dessert. The whole bowl has 900 calories and 26 grams of protein, so great for a winter bulk.

Christmas soup. It's a Czech tradition to eat fish soup on Christmas Eve, so I decided to slightly modify one of my recipes (Lohikeitto - Finnish salmon soup, it's now also in my updated cookbook). Made with potatoes, turnip, black carrot, white yoghurt and salmon. Instructions: Cook the vegetables first, then take some out and blend the rest to make a thick, creamy soup. Divide a salmon fillet in two parts, cook one in the soup, add yoghurt and blend everything. Sautee the other part of the salmon in a pan and serve in the soup with the cooked vegetables. Approximately equal parts of vegetables (150 grams each), 100 grams of yoghurt and 250 grams of keta salmon add up to 666 kcal and 65 grams of protein. That's enough for some 3-4 servings.

Castagnaccio. I had some old chestnuts that were too hard to eat, so I decided to boil and puree them and use the chestnut puree to make this Italian cake. The dark base is chestnut puree with chestnut honey, the light cream is ricotta whipped with egg, chestnut honey and vanilla. First I baked the dark layer for 20 minutes, then I covered it with the light layer and baked it for 30 more. And I used some chopped baked chestnuts as a topping. The original recipe contains more ingredients but it is tasty even when you make it this simple. 425 calories and 19 grams of protein.

My winter baking series continues. A while ago I saw a post that asked "Why are Swedish Pepparkakor called Pepparkakor when they don't contain any pepper?" I thought: "What a retarded question... obviously; because you didn't put it there." The real question is, why wouldn't you put pepper in something that's called Pepparkakor? So I did exactly that. I bought a small bag of dark red Kampot peppercorn and started baking. The dough is really simple: 1. mix 40 grams of whole-grain flour, baking powder, crushed peppercorns, cardamom, ginger, cinnamon, cloves or any other spices you like (allspice, star anise, nutmeg, etc.) 2. Melt 15 grams of butter and about 15 grams of good quality honey. I used unfiltered honey I bought from a farmers' market in Slovenia, it contains honey, pollen, propolis and royal jelly. 3. Knead the dough and let it chill overnight. 4. Roll it out and bake for 10 minutes.

Almond shortbreads - a luxury treat after dinner or with coffee. Ingredients: 40 grams of French butter (mix of salted from Isigny and unsalted from Charentes-Poitou) 110 grams of high-protein almond flour (100% almonds) 10 grams of French chestnut honey 1 gram of vanilla 1 gram of tonka beans Preparation: 1. Soften the butter and mix it with honey. 2. Mix the almond flour with the spices. 3. Combine the wet and dry ingredients and knead the dough. 4. The dough will be quite dry and crumbly; wrap it in foil or paper and press it to form a block. 5. Let it cool in your fridge for about 30 minutes. 6. Pre-heat the oven to about 175 C / 350 F. 7. Bake them for 10-15 minutes, depending on how brown you want them to be. 128 calories and 7 grams of protein per one piece.

Gingerbats 150 grams of whole grain spelt flour (or any other flour of your preference) 50 grams of chestnut or other dark honey 1 egg 3 grams of baking powder 10 grams of gingerbread spice mix (or any spices you want) Mix everything, roll out the dough, cut out shapes and bake for 10 minutes; simple. 732 calories and 27 grams of protein (43 calories and 1.6 grams of protein per one piece)

But for whatever reason, even those with the PGI (Protected Geographical Indication) label can contain ingredients such as glucose syrup or palm oil that certainly weren't in the original recipe and that I don't want to eat. So once again, I had to make my own. Mix one egg, 50 grams of flour, 50 grams of almond flour, 25 grams of ground hazelnuts, 25 grams of ground walnuts, 20 grams of honey and whatever winter spices you like. Soften (but don‚Äôt melt) the butter. 3. Make a dough and shape it. 4. Let it chill in a fridge for 30 minutes. 5. Bake for 15 minutes or until slightly brown. Do not try to shape the dough when cold, it will crack and break. 314 calories, 14 grams of protein.

Repost of the last year's Christmas dinner from my cookbook. I have a lot of lamb plov cooked so I just can't be arsed to cook anything new tonight. BOAR WITH RED CABBAGE PUREE AND POTATO PANCAKES Ingredients: Boar meat Mulled wine Red cabbage Rosehip jam Quark / curd cheese Flour Egg Potatoes Gingerbread spices Preparation ‚Äì meat and cabbage: Wash the meat and put it in a slow cooker. Pour in the wine but don‚Äôt fully cover the meat. Cook for at least six hours. Cut the cabbage into smaller pieces. Place them in a pot, pour in the rest of the wine and cook until soft and the wine has evaporated. Add some unsweetened jam to the cabbage and blend it in a blender until smooth and creamy. Preparation ‚Äì potato pancakes: Cook about 200 grams of potatoes in boiling water. Peel and mash them. In a bowl, mix 30 grams of flour, 1 egg, 200 to 250 grams of curd cheese, some gingerbread spices and the potatoes. Shape the mixture into pancakes and roast on a pan on a thin layer of butter.

Christmas dinner. In accordance with the oldest European traditions, my meat of choice was once again wild boar and the recipe I used as inspiration was Danish √Üblefl√¶sk. How to cook it: 1. Get some lean boar meat (or pork if you can't get boar), put it in a slow cooker, pour in some vintage cider (not too much, don't cover the meat) and cook. I cooked it for 5 hours. 2. Strain the leftover broth/cider, add some dark forest honey and cinnamon, slice some apples and potatoes and cook them in it. 3. Melt some butter on a pan and saute a sliced onion. 4. Once the potatoes and apples are cooked, pour everything into the pan and reduce it to a thick syrup. 5. Add the sliced meat to cover it with the sauce and serve everything together. 523 calories, 39 grams of protein. Or more, if you serve yourself more meat, which I recommend.

If you have a camera, I strongly recommend you take it out and try some landscape photography, especially with a longer lens. Why? 1. Walking is cardio, but while on a treadmill you will get bored after ten minutes, outdoors you can wander for hours and always discover something new. 2. A longer lens will force you to find interesting details and therefore to focus on what's around you. That will train your mind to become immune to distractions. 3. Once you get into it, you will be able to spend hours wandering around looking for something interesting without thinking about food, the time, your phone, etc. In other words, it is almost like a meditation combined with cardio that I strongly recommend to everyone. You do not even have to travel far; while a wide-angle lens needs generally interesting scenery, a colourful bush or a group of leaves can wait for you even in the nearest park.

"Four Simple Compositional Tips" That will improve not only your photographs but your entire life if you apply them correctly. 1. "Fill The Frame With What You Love" In photography that applies to the photograph itself, but approach everything else the same way. Your day has 24 hours. What do you fill them with? Is most of it what you want to focus on (pun intended) or just random shit that happens to be there? Which brings us to the second point. 2. "Remove What Distracts You". If you don't want it to be there, remove it. It could be a dry branch, a beer can that someone left there, or anything in your life that costs you time, money or energy even though it's not what you really want. 3. "Create Depth With Layers" Since a photograph rarely shows only one object, a well-composed one will smoothly guide you through the frame, leading you from one important subject to another. 4. "Follow Composition Rules" Knowing where to place what will create a clear path that will help you find everything in its place.

The obvious problem with a lot of these moral truisms is that often time they aren‚Äôt very true at all. The most widely known ‚Äúdebunker‚Äù of moral truisms was Friedrich Nietzsche. After all, Nietzsche proposed the idea that power was something everyone should strive to achieve, and Nietzsche was also the person who opposed the idea of envy being a bad thing. Nietzsche‚Äôs argumentation against these moral truisms was so important and valuable, that it influenced practically every philosopher and scholar on the planet. One could just imagine what the world would have looked like if Nietzsche kept his mouth shut. A contemporary moral truism is a notion that we should be tolerant of everything ‚Äúas long as it‚Äôs not hurting anyone‚Äù and that we should just ‚Äúlet people enjoy things‚Äù Like most moral truisms they seem obvious on a surface level and as a bonus, they are simple enough to remember and tweet. But unfortunately, life isn‚Äôt always as simple as a tweet. Just because certain actions aren‚Äôt physically hurting others doesn‚Äôt mean that they are okay, and by conditioning the population to stay quiet on such matters the inevitable outcome is that these destructive antics flourish and become the norm which results in a population of village id!ots. Therefore yes, we should let people enjoy things not because all pleasure is good but because everyone is responsible for their life and actions. That being said, we should not become oblivious to reality and accept all forms of behavior which are evidentially destructive just so we don‚Äôt offend anyone. Such actions are not just pointless but a rejection of reality, innate survival instincts, and anti-human at the core.

A moral truism refers to a proposition or statement within the realm of ethics or morality that is considered self-evidently true, universally accepted, and requiring little or no further justification or argumentation. They are typically characterized by their intuitive and straightforward nature, with their validity being perceived as inherently evident or obvious. Moral truisms are as the name applies, widely accepted and often repeated like a mantra, and like with a mantra the person repeating them doesn‚Äôt always quite clearly understand what he is saying nor does he ever question the validity of such statements.

https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fnut.2023.1173488/full I‚Äôm sure that everyone here is aware of the fact that a person with BMI >25 doesn‚Äôt necessarily have to be fat (even though most of them are). Well, you should also be aware that the opposite is not only possible but actually much more common - to be specific, 1 in 3 people with a healthy BMI is too fat (you could describe them as ‚Äúskinny fat‚Äù).

Losing weight is an old and idiotic way of optimising health. Most people aren‚Äôt too fat so much as they‚Äôre under-muscled. You don‚Äôt want to lose weight, you want to build more muscle. The more muscle you have, the harder your metabolism needs to work to repair and retain that muscle. By lifting heavy and on a daily basis, you‚Äôll eventually get to certain point of musculoskeletal mass where your maintenance calories will be high but you won‚Äôt be getting fatter; you‚Äôll be able to eat a lot more while still not gaining any excess fat, because you‚Äôre lifting so regularly and have developed your muscles to such an extent that your metabolism is on fire all day. And when the gut is forced to work more efficiently to feed your developing muscles, everything in the body begins to work better. Your neurotransmitters which your brain uses as reward systems and to communicate with the rest of your body are made in your gut. The muscles also have their own hormonal system which, when stimulated through stretching and contracting, literally have anti-depressant effects on the brain. Build more muscle ought to be the phrase to replace the dated and dumb ‚Äúlose more weight‚Äù.

I‚Äôm forwarding this post with a comment. 1. Yes, most people (at least in the west) are too fat. Yes, most people should lose some weight. If you have a 40‚Äù waist, then sorry, but you are fat and no amount of muscle mass is going to compensate for it. (To put it in a perspective; Ronnie Coleman had a 36‚Äù waist while weighing over 300 lbs. An average US male has a 40‚Äù waist while weighing slightly under 200 lbs.) Not to mention that if you‚Äôre already overweight because of carrying an excessive amount of fat and gain some extra muscle mass on top of it, certain parts of your body such as your knee or hip joints will suffer even more, making certain activities such as running even more difficult and dangerous (also, for example, the carbon bike frame I rode last weekend can carry a maximum of 275 lbs and that includes your clothes, helmet, backpack, etc.) The next thing is that way too many people just love to use muscle building and/or strength training as a convenient excuse to eat like pigs and remain fat because ‚Äúthey need energy for their workouts‚Äù or whatever, ignoring the fact that half of the energy is used just on moving their own body around. 2. Yes, Blair is absolutely right that if you have more muscle mass, being in a calorie deficit is easier, you can eat more and lose more fat without constantly starving. No objections here whatsoever. This applies especially to women, who, instead of doing a few deadlifts they‚Äôll rather eat half a grapefruit and a kale smoothie for lunch and then feel like shit and eventually give up and eat a tub of ice cream. Or, if they somehow manage to stick to their diet, they‚Äôll end up being skinny fat and weak so they‚Äôll wear a smaller dress size but still feel like shit. Another thing is that being stronger means you can lift heavier weights which means you‚Äôll burn more calories during your lifting session (not that that‚Äôs the best way to burn calories, but still‚Ä¶). 3. What I recommend is a combination of both. Carrying extra 20 lbs for 10 miles burns the same number of calories regardless of whether those 20 lbs are in your gut or in your backpack. There‚Äôs even a formula which you can use to calculate the number of extra calories you‚Äôll burn by carrying a certain weight for a certain distance. Take advantage of that but also take advantage of the fact that if those extra 20 lbs are in your backpack rather then in your gut, you can always take it off and leave it at home when you feel like riding a carbon fibre bike.

1 DAY, 250 KM / 155 MI No supplements, no isotonic drinks, no energy drinks, no magnesium, not even a fucking multivitamin. Why? For the same reason why I did it three times on a mountain bike; because it can be done. To prove a point. To make a statement. Doing something like that is from 90% a matter of simply deciding to do it instead of worrying whether you have the right bicycle, the right clothes, the right supplements, whether it's not too hot, not too cold, not too dry, not too humid, etc. And no, I'm not saying that some supplements may not help, just like it helps if you're riding a carbon composite gravel bike instead of a full-suspension MTB, but they're not what makes or breaks it. Of course, it should be assumed that you're eating well and not stopping on the way to buy Coke and hot dogs, but a solid diet should give you enough macro and micronutrients for most activities, there's no reason why a healthy person should take more pills than his 90 y.o. granny.

It never ceases to amaze me how many people are dethatched from reality. Ever since I got back to training in commercial gyms I started getting approached by bros who ask me what my eating and training is like, and every time I answer I get the same questions back. ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt you get bored of eating just chicken and rice or beef and rice?‚Äù ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt get annoyed that you have to weigh everything before you eat it?‚Äù ‚ÄúShouldn‚Äôt you try to have more balance in your life?‚Äù The simple answer is no. I would much rather live an ‚Äúunbalanced‚Äù life while looking as best as I can and being as strong as possible than live a ‚Äúbalanced‚Äù and ‚Äúrealistic‚Äù life while looking like any other dude on the street. Unfortunately, this isn‚Äôt something most people understand. Being ‚Äúrealistic‚Äù and ‚Äúhaving balance‚Äù is mutually exclusive with being exceptional. Therefore, you have to pick between the two. Do you want to be ‚Äúrealistic‚Äù and ‚Äúhave balance‚Äù or do you want to be great? Because you sure as hell can‚Äôt have both.

I feel like I need to clarify something: Every now and then I come across some coach or nutritionist talking about this stupid ‚Äú80/20 rule diet‚Äù. Yea, there is something called 80/20 rule (also known as Pareto Principle, I wrote a page about it in my book, get it here https://vegard.gumroad.com/l/reinventingwesterncuisine if you don‚Äôt have it yet), but that rule says that 20 % of your actions result in 80 % of your achievements. NOT that you should only make 80% effort, NOR that you should be satisfied with an 80% result. If I compare it to BJJ or any other combat sport; obviously, you will not win every single time, but that does not mean that you should intentionally give up and lose 20% of your fights. I hope everyone understands it now.

Related to today's recipe, I'm posting "The Decalogue of Artusi's cuisine", that I find useful and inspiring not only when cooking Italian food: 1. RESPECT NATURAL INGREDIENTS Love the beautiful and the good wherever they are and do not tolerate seeing God's grace torn to pieces. 2. USE QUALITY INGREDIENTS Always choose natural raw ingredients of the finest quality because this will make you look good. 3. USE SEASONAL INGREDIENTS Vegetables should be prepared at the peak of their harvest time when they are inexpensive, but they should be chosen based on good quality and reasonable ripeness. Use only healthy and ripe fruit depending on the season. 4. KEEP IT SIMPLE My kitchen is inclined towards the simple and delicate, staying as far away as possible from foods that are too complicated and overly composed of various elements, thereby embarrassing the stomach. 5. BE PASSIONATE, CAREFUL AND PRECISE If you don't have the pretension to become a restaurant chef, all you need to succeed is passion, a lot of attention to detail, and precision. 6. PRACTICE WITH PATIENCE Have the patience to give it a try. If at first you don't succeed, do not be dismayed; good will and persistence win. 7. VARIETY, BUT RESPECTING THE TERRITORY AND SEASONALITY Here is how I would make a minestrone: kitchen masters should modify it in their own way and in accordance with their taste, the country, and the vegetables found nearby. 8. IF YOU VARY, DO IT WITH SIMPLICITY AND GOOD TASTE All dishes can be prepared in various ways according to the creativity of those who make them. When changing them at will, however, never lose sight of the simple, delicate, and pleasant flavors, so it really sits in the good taste of those who prepare them. 9. ENHANCE THE "POOR CUISINE" This soup that, for modesty, is given the nickname of a peasant girl, I am convinced will be appreciated by all. 10. ALWAYS BE WARY OF ALL COOKBOOKS (EVEN MINE) Careful of books about this art. Most of them are misleading and incomprehensible, at most, you will be able to draw some useful notions when you know the art better.

Maccheroni Alla Bolognese üáÆüáπ This is not the most famous recipe submitted to the Bologna Chamber of Commerce in 1982. This is a recipe from Pellegrino Artusi's book 'La scienza in cucina e l'arte di mangiar bene', published in 1891. It does not contain wine or tomatoes but suggests adding liver (a good opportunity for those who otherwise don't like organ meats) or mushrooms. Preparation: 1. Chop one carrot, one onion and two celery stalks (100 grams from each). 2. Melt a few grams of butter or lard in a pan and saute the vegetables. Move them to a pot and brown about 500 grams of ground veal. 3. Mix the meat with the vegetables and slow cook for at least three hours. 4. Stir in some liver pate, dried mushroom powder and cream and cook for another 30 minutes. (If using fresh liver, cook it with the meat.) 5. Serve with some pasta - I used Garganelli, which is egg pasta from the Emilia-Romagna region. 6. Add grated Parmigiano and nutmeg. 440 calories and 40 grams of protein (the recipe equals 4 servings)

Serbian Risotto. That's neither Serbian nor a risotto. Mindfuck. This recipe comes from communist-ruled Czechoslovakia and for a long time, when you said you ate or cooked a risotto, everyone assumed it was this. However, instead of Carnaroli or similar Italian rice used for risotto, which was not available (just as many other western ingredients), this was cooked with normal long-grain rice we imported from our comrades in China or Vietnam. To simulate the creamy texture of starchy short-grain rice, this rice was simply overcooked to the point when it became watery and sticky. The final result somewhat resembles a Serbian/Balkan dish ƒêuveƒç/Ghivetch, however, that one is prepared with different vegetables. So if you search for Serbian dishes on Tasteatlas or another similar website, you will not find this. The benefit of this recipe (compared to an Italian risotto) is, that even a stupid communist could cook it without screwing something up. 466 calories, 51 grams of protein. Recipe in the comments.

cleaned_message: Maslenitsa What the West knows as Pancake Tuesday was (and in Eastern Europe still is) a Pagan celebration of spring with the round, yellow pancakes or crepes symbolising the sun. Therefore I decided to make them extra yellow by adding some spices normally used in golden (turmeric) milk. 1. Get some milk and warm it up. 2. Add a generous amount of turmeric, ginger, star anise, cardamom, vanilla and saffron. 3. Let the milk infuse for some time, then strain it. 4. Then make crepes the same way you'd make them with regular milk (I already have a recipe in my PDF cookbook) 5. Drizzle some unfiltered raw honey on them, I used honey from Slovenia which contains propolis and royal jelly. Pro tip: if you make the batter thin and only cook them from one side, the other side will remain yellow and shiny. 194 calories and 12 grams of protein per one crepe without filling.

I will elaborate on the above. It may be a surprise for some, but fruits and vegetables are natural foods. They have seasons (and so do other foods, for example, some dairy products). Especially if you have a farmers‚Äô market nearby, you may have noticed that they don‚Äôt sell the same things year-round. If you want to get the freshest, ripest and at the same time cheapest food, accept that and buy what‚Äôs currently in season. In my country, that‚Äôs currently apples, turnips, beetroots, parsley, parsnip, carrot and plenty of leafy greens such as Brussels sprouts, kale or cabbage. Yes, I live in the capital city and thanks to that, if I want to buy a pack of fresh cherries in February, I can have them. But when I can get a kilo of apples for ‚Ç¨0.55 while a kilo of cherries would cost me ‚Ç¨29.50, do I want to? Sure, if you just improved your deadlift PR and want to celebrate, by all means go and treat yourself with ‚Ç¨10 worth of fresh cherries, but if you just want to get some quick carbs before your workout, apples will do.
Imagine living in England and complaining that you can only buy three packs of raspberries in mid-fucking-February. Go eat some winter apples and stop whining you spoiled brats‚Ä¶

Another recipe prepared from the same Irish bacon: oven-baked bacon with leeks in cheddar sauce and violet potatoes. üáÆüá™ üá¨üáß 1. Hand-shred the bacon (you can also use cooked ham), chop the leeks and mix in a deep baking dish. 2. Take the bacon broth from the pot in which you cooked the meat. Dilute it with water if it's too salty. 3. Grate some aged cheddar cheese, the stronger the taste, the better. I used 15 Fields Irish cheddar made from raw summer milk. 4. Bacon and Cabbage üáÆüá™ I brought this nice big cut of lean bacon from Ireland so I decided to make this traditional dish. 1. Soak the bacon overnight in cold water, then discard the water (it will be very salty). 2. Cut the cabbage, add it to the pot with bacon, cover with water and cook for about 1.5 hours. 3. Remove the cabbage and meat from the water, add some crushed black pepper and allspice to the cabbage and put it in the oven for about 10 minutes to dry it a bit. 4. Put some barley in the bacon broth and cook it. 5. Strain the barley but keep the broth. 6. Mix the broth with some creme fraiche and freshly chopped parsley leaves. 555 calories and 56 grams of protein

The customs are all strange in there, they'll dance and shout with glee; But in the morning, sad they wake, - it's Pharmacology! Sly salesmen sell you shiny toys, they're custom made for you; They make you feel so wonderful, but so do brothels too. They'll sell you love in plastic wrap, it's soulless and it's cheap; You'll sow these seeds of emptiness, and this is what you'll reap. The old stone walls are falling down, and nothings built to last; You won't find mothers cooking here, it's purgatory's grasp. cleaned_message: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6407755/#!po=14.1509 For those who still don‚Äôt fully understand what‚Äôs wrong with refined oils. Many people try to argument in favour of refined vegetable oils because they have a higher smoke point than let‚Äôs say butter (which is true, but so does asbestos and nobody eats it‚Ä¶) You see; the problem with refined oils isn‚Äôt in what you do with them but what the factory does with them. Typical deep-frying temperature is about 170-180 Celsius degrees. The smoke point of rapeseed oil, which is a common frying oil, is between 210 C and 250 C degrees. Most foods are deep-fried for about 5 minutes, rarely more than 10. However, when the oil is deodorized in the factory, it can be heated up to 270 C and what‚Äôs more important, this process takes over an hour rather than a few minutes. Which means the fats in the oil had oxidised long before it has been filled in bottles and left the factory and even if you used it cold in a salad, it would still be bad for you.
url_title: The effect of refining process on the physicochemical properties and micronutrients of rapeseed oils
url_description: Information on the physicochemical variability in rapeseed oil from different varieties during each refining process is lacking. Our purpose was to investigate the physicochemical properties, micronutrients and oxidative stability of the oil extracted ...

Related to the previous post: the 80/20 diet rule (when 80% of what you eat are healthy, nutrient rich meals and the remaining 20% is whatever you want) is bullshit. I‚Äôll explain why. The idea behind this diet is, that nobody is able to eat 100% healthy food 24/7/365. Which is true. However: Imagine you have a factory that produces something. Every factory will inevitably produce some defective products. But that does not mean that if you find out that 20% of your products can be defective and you can still make some profit, you will intentionally start sabotaging 1/5 of your production just because you can get away with it. Yes, you may even have some acceptable quality level, but that will be your worst case scenario and you will still try to minimise your defect rate instead of trying to match your AQL day after day. Equally, you won‚Äôt find an athlete who will intentionally lose 20% of his competitions, a lawyer who will intentionally lose 20% of his court cases or a surgeon who will intentionally fail 20% of his surgeries. So why should you approach your diet differently?

Balance is cope. The word balance is a code word utilized as a justification by people that do not have the willpower to commit to anything fully. If you are in a position that you do not want to be in, whether that be because you are carrying too much fat, too little muscle, being in overall bad shape, not making enough money, etc. the last thing you should concern yourself with is balance. Worry about balance once you achieve the results you want to achieve and once you have enough positive lifestyle habits to balance out the negative ones; instead of justifying your lack of results as something which is admirable.

Like I said many times; if the only thing you have in common with your supposed ally is a common enemy, the moment the enemy is gone, so is your alliance. Even a broken clock is right twice a day and even a complete retard can say something ‚Äúbased‚Äù every now and then.

The enemy of our enemy is not our friend. In our contemporary society, it is a widely accepted idea that anyone who shares our values or viewpoints in life or has a common enemy is by definition our ally, and therefore someone we should defend in any and all circumstances. But this couldn‚Äôt be further from the truth. This suggests that temporary alliances can be formed based solely on a shared disdain for a common foe, without any consideration for the long-term consequences or the true intentions of the supposed ally. If we look into history, Julius Caesar and Pompey Magnus were at one point incredibly close allies, simply because they shared a common enemy and they had a surface-level mutual goal, but that didn‚Äôt prevent them from waging a bloody war against each other.

It‚Äôs good to wake up on New Year‚Äôs Day at 8:15 AM and not feel like shit. But it‚Äôs also good to use this opportunity clarify some things about sleep. When you should naturally fall asleep or wake up is determined by your circadian rhythm (if you‚Äôve never heard about it, look it up). This also applies to all animals - they don‚Äôt use an alarm and they know when to wake up and so should you. If you need an electronic device to make an irritating sound to wake up, it means you‚Äôre waking up unnaturally early. For example, I wake up between 8 AM and 9 AM regardless of when I go to bed. If other people want to wake up at 4:30, that‚Äôs their choice, I don‚Äôt give a fuck. If your job forces you to wake up earlier than you want to, it may be in your best long-term interest to either change your work hours or your job. There‚Äôs one more reason why there‚Äôs no need to obsess over waking up at a particular hour. For example, if you live in Prague (CZ) and woke up at 8:15 like myself, you woke up 15 minutes after the sunrise. But if you live in Brest (F) and woke up at 8:15, you woke up 45 minutes before the sunrise. And if you live in Troms√∏ (N), you‚Äôll see your first sunrise of 2023 in two weeks from now. If you travel a lot, you may experience a sort of jet lag even within the same time zone exactly for this reason. It‚Äôs also the reason why it‚Äôs easier to wake up early in summer than in winter. But your circadian rhythm uses the sun as a reference, not time, which is just a made-up number. Which means that someone who likes to brag about waking up earlier than you may actually wake up later, when you compare it to the sun rather than the clock. Whenever you wake up though, make sure you spend the day doing something productive (I‚Äôm heading for a hike in two hours from now).

When it comes to food, many people, including those on the right side of the political spectrum, are guilty of "xenophilia". That means, they think something is better just because it's exotic, looking down at European food and dismissing it as "bland" and "boring". Well, first of all, this "bland" cooking is more difficult because it demands high-quality ingredients. When I season the meat with so many spices you can't tell whether you're eating a chicken or a turkey, that meat could as well come from week-old roadkill and you wouldn't know (that's why countries known for using the most spices are also often known for willing to eat everything that moves, including all kinds of diseased bushmeat and other vile stuff). And second; nobody disparages Italian cuisine that can be just as simple - perhaps because "Cacio e pepe" or "Pappa al pomodoro" sounds fancier than "pasta with cheese and black pepper" or "stale bread soaked in tomato sauce".

British cuisine is good. Change my mind. Turkey in my classic white sauce (broth, yoghurt, creme fraiche, egg), oven-roasted root vegetables, potatoes and Brussels sprouts. 592 calories, 46 grams of protein.

N√ºrnberger Elisenlebkuchen I like German Lebkuchen. But for whatever reason, even those with the PGI (Protected Geographical Indication) label can contain ingredients such as glucose syrup or palm oil that certainly weren't in the original recipe and that I don't want to eat. So once again, I had to make my own. Mix one egg, 50 grams of flour, 50 grams of almond flour, 25 grams of ground hazelnuts, 25 grams of ground walnuts, 20 grams of honey and whatever winter spices you like. Make a dough, roll it out, cut out some shapes and bake them for about 15 minutes. If you want to make some with chocolate glaze, melt some 100% chocolate, dilute it with water and add some honey or spices if you want to. Then brush it over the gingerbreads. 822 calories and 47 grams of protein (mainly thanks to my high-protein almond flour).

Castagnaccio. I had some old chestnuts that were too hard to eat, so I decided to boil and puree them and use the chestnut puree to make this Italian cake. The dark base is chestnut puree with chestnut honey, the light cream is ricotta whipped with egg, chestnut honey and vanilla. First I baked the dark layer for 20 minutes, then I covered it with the light layer and baked it for 30 more. And I used some chopped baked chestnuts as a topping. The original recipe contains more ingredients but it is tasty even when you make it this simple. 425 calories and 19 grams of protein.

Maybe it's that relative you forgot to buy a thing for, perhaps a gift that's running late for delivery, or perhaps it's a sense of guilt that "we haven't gotten them enough". Much of this feeling is unnatural, and doesn't readily exist in paleo or traditional cultures across time and around the world. No, what you're feeling is artificially encoded into the holiday zeitgeist by the merchant class who want you to spend every last dollar to offset your guilt. If you try and kick this feeling and go without, it may come back to bite you at crunch time, as this consumerism has been so heavily driven into us since our grandparents were children. PRESERVE fruits and vegetables in jams and chutneys, or pickled in brine, or herbs from your garden in oil. Test out new recipes and if they suck, well at least they're obviously home made. SCAVENGE for things in op shops or charity stores that remind you of the person. Most people have a fondness for the loved and second-lived, more than something that's fresh from a plastic farm in China. All the while you're building skills, fond memories, relationship with your family, and sharing this passion with the recipient who can't help but feel that love. Tell the supermarket goblins to get f*cked this Christmas and take a different path. Xoxo -Mack

The 9 small Pepparkakor you see in the photo contain 280 calories and 5.5 grams of protein, but that's not really the point since it's a festive treat and not a post-workout meal. The point is that you can bake all kinds of traditional foods without sugar (which wasn't available in Europe for most of its history) or any other unhealthy or artificial ingredients (the original Pepparkakor were considered so healthy, they were sold in pharmacies). When it comes to their taste, you can make them more or less sweet by changing the amount of honey. Next to that, you can experiment with different ratios and combinations of spices - mine mainly smell of cardamom but I can definitely taste the peppercorns in them as well as hints of ginger.

My winter baking series continues. A while ago I saw a post that asked "Why are Swedish Pepparkakor called Pepparkakor when they don't contain any pepper?" I thought: "What a retarded question... obviously; because you didn't put it there." The real question is, why wouldn't you put pepper in something that's called Pepparkakor? So I did exactly that. I bought a small bag of dark red Kampot peppercorn and started baking. The dough is really simple: 1. mix 40 grams of whole-grain flour, baking powder, crushed peppercorns, cardamom, ginger, cinnamon, cloves or any other spices you like (allspice, star anise, nutmeg, etc.) 2. Melt 15 grams of butter and about 15 grams of good quality honey. I used unfiltered honey I bought from a farmers' market in Slovenia, it contains honey, pollen, propolis and royal jelly. 3. Knead the dough and let it chill overnight. 4. Roll it out and bake for 10 minutes.

An improvised fusion recipe - let's call it a Hungarian Bolognese. 1. Slow-cook some beef, strain and keep the broth. 2. Cook some pasta. 3. You'll end up with pasta with pulled beef in spicy pepper sauce, or something between Hungarian stew and Italian Bolognese. 730 calories, 56 grams of protein.

On November 11th, most of the world celebrates the end of the First World War. In former Austria-Hungary, it's not too much of a thing (after all, it's a war we started), but we have a better tradition; a goose feast. It originated in the Roman Empire where it was celebrated as the end of the harvest period and two of the most significant traditions are eating goose (associated with Mars, the Roman god of war, it was nicknamed "Avis Martis") and drinking new wine. How to prepare it: 1. Get some goose breast, it has a better calorie-to-protein ratio (pretty much on par with chicken) and doesn't need as much time to roast as a whole goose. 2. Crush some pink peppercorn and salt in a mortar or grinder, sprinkle the goose with it and then pour some red wine over it. I used Blaufr√§nkisch wine, which comes from Hungary. 3. Cover with aluminium foil and roast for 70 minutes. Then remove the foil and roast for 20 more.

I covered this in one of my previous posts, but even gaining 1lbs of muscle per month is extremely unrealistic. Therefore if you go on a 10 week bulk and you end up putting 20-25lbs how much of that do you realistically think is muscle? It would probably equate to 10% if you are lucky. Most of the weight people put on during a bulk is fat, water and glycogen, and what most people (do not) realize is that being full of water and glycogen (and even fat to a smaller degree) makes people look better. It makes them look fuller, bigger and more powerful and as a result people perceive that as muscle, only to get disappointed after a difficult cut when they realize they are practically at the same place they started originally. And no, you don‚Äôt want to set your expectations on bulking based on the results of Chris Bumstead. Chris Bumstead is genetic anomaly, one of the best built people in the world and also Chris has abs in his off season, most people don‚Äôt have abs when they are in shape.

It feels like I have to cover the topic of bulking every 6 months as this remains one of the most common topics I get requested on covering as well as one of the most common topics I get questioned around. Similarly, there is reason why everyone that has trained for a long enough period of time has a horror story involved with bulking. There is also a reason why I haven‚Äôt bulked in over 4 years. The reason is simple; bulking for most people isn‚Äôt a viable strategy for a significant increase in muscle mass.

The dough will be quite dry and crumbly; wrap it in foil or paper and press it to form a block. 5. Let it cool in your fridge for about 30 minutes. 6. Pre-heat the oven to about 175 C / 350 F. 7. Bake them for 10-15 minutes, depending on how brown you want them to be. 128 calories and 7 grams of protein per one piece.

https://www.fda.gov/food/ingredients-additives-gras-packaging-guidance-documents-regulatory-information/food-defect-levels-handbook FDA Food Defect Levels Handbook. ‚ÄúLevels of natural or unavoidable defects in foods that present no health hazards for humans‚Äù The document describes possible defects in food, including insect infestation. For example, 100 grams of mushrooms you buy from a supermarket can contain up to 20 maggots. And these are the FDA regulations, so the chance of infestation of any organic food that hasn‚Äôt been treated with insecticides (such as fruit from your garden or wild mushrooms from a forest) will be even higher. Again; I don‚Äôt endorse eating insects by choice, but don‚Äôt think you‚Äôre not eating them already (unless you only eat processed food - I assume there‚Äôs a very little chance of finding any insects in let‚Äôs say Coca-Cola).

Lots of stereotypes about peoples are based on factual observations that are generalised, but some are completely false. If you look at the false ones, you may notice a pattern - many are the exact opposite of reality and are perpetuated by media depictions rather than people's lived experiences: -British people have bad teeth (better dental health than most western countries inc. USA) -France is cowardly in war (they win far more wars than America for eg) -Rural white Americans are inbred (among the least inbred in the world) -British aristocracy are inbred (also among the least inbred in the world) -Blondes are less intelligent (Europe-wide increased levels of blondism correlate with higher IQ) Other negative stereotypes about the above groups are based on actual realities, even if they aren't necessarily always representative, such as: -British people have bad food -Americans are fat But these sorts of stereotypes derive from historic interactions between peoples leading to such generalisations. The ones above do not - they were manufactured. Think about why.

Now to the Soul Cakes recipe, which will suffice for 7 small cakes. Get 40 grams of butter (I used my salted butter) and 40 grams of powdered milk and mix them together to create a paste. Then add a small egg yolk. Sift 110 grams of whole-grain flour into a bowl. Add allspice, ginger, cinnamon and nutmeg and mix well. Combine the dry ingredients with the wet paste and mix. At this point, the dough will most likely be dry and crumbly. Warm 50 ml of milk, add 10 grams of honey and mix. Pour it into the dough. Add 15 grams of raisins (you can cut them in halves or quarters) and knead until you create one piece of dough. Roll the dough out and cut out circles or whatever shapes you prefer. Preheat your oven to 175 C or 350 F and bake the cakes for 15 minutes. Then take them out, flip them and bake for 5 more minutes so that they're equally crunchy from both sides but still slightly soft in the centre. The 7 cakes have 997 calories and 31 grams of protein, which is not bad at all for a dessert. To balance the macro, you can whip some curd cheese with a teaspoon of honey or some spices and eat it with the cakes. As for the taste, they taste completely natural and have a nice smell of wholegrain flour and hints of spices (this time I played it safe with the spices, the next time I'll use more). The recipe seems pretty versatile, you can easily make them with other fruits, cocoa, nuts, etc. But even this basic version is something I'd gladly buy from a bakery.

Since almost 2/3 of you seem to bake, here's the result of my first baking experiment, for which I chose "Soul Cakes" - a simple recipe from medieval England and Ireland. My goal was to test whether sugar could be replaced with powdered milk (although given their origin, it's safe to assume they were originally made without sugar anyway). The answer is simple; yes. 100 grams of semi-skimmed powdered milk contain 430 calories and 31 grams of protein, so the macro ratios are the same as in milk, only 10x concentrated. Therefore it's not only better than sugar but also better than flour. The milk has 45% "sugar" content, however, the sugar we're talking about here is lactose, which is a disaccharide consisting of galactose and glucose. It does not contain any fructose, which means there's no risk of developing a fatty liver. Lactose is about 30% as sweet as sucrose (table sugar) and has about 10 points lower glycemic index.

Hortobagyi Palacsinta This one is already in my cookbook ( https://vegard.gumroad.com/l/reinventingwesterncuisine ) but today I decided to make it again and simplify the process. Add tomato paste, hot pepper paste, red paprika, water and let it simmer for some 10 minutes. For a milder taste, you can stir in some creme fraiche or sour cream. To make the sauce, simply blend a roasted pepper with creme fraiche. Stuff the meat in a large crepe, pour on some sauce and garnish with some freshly chopped parsley. Since the meat is basically a kind of beef ragout, you can serve it the same way you would serve Bolognese or Makaronia Me Kima. 783 calories and 74 grams of protein

cleaned_message: I was asked to make something sweet, so here you go; a baked baby pumpkin stuffed with curd cheese, apple, vanilla, cinnamon and walnuts. I used Topaz apples which are native to the Czech Republic and are great even raw (their taste is crisp and intense) but you can use whatever variety you prefer. When preparing the stuffing, I recommend grating the apples, dusting them with vanilla and cinnamon and pressing them to release the juice. Don't ask me for the chemistry behind it, but the combination of vanilla and cinnamon makes apples taste much sweeter - you can test it yourself. Once stuffed, bake the pumpkin in an oven for about 30 minutes or until they soften and the skin starts getting brown. If you want a more intense taste, you can replace the curd cheese with some soft goat cheese. Since the dessert is mostly fruit and vegetable, it has only 140 calories and 8 grams of protein.

Most of my dishes can be easily modified (after all, 260 calories is not much) so here are a few examples: More protein: Add more meat (to the point when it will look like a stew) or eggs. More fat: Use meat with higher fat content, grate / melt some cheese in the mushroom sauce, add some heavy cream or melted butter. More carbs: Eat it with some toasted bread or add more potatoes (mushrooms are mostly water - everyone who tried to dry some will know this).

If mushroom dishes have one thing in common, then it's the fact that they usually look pretty disgusting. The taste is worth it though. Toast wild parasol (or any) mushrooms on salted butter, transfer to a pot with a sliced potato, cover with water and cook. Don't use more water than necessary to keep it thick. When cooked, blend with a hand blender. It's like making a creamy mushroom soup but with less water. Meatloaf with Norwegian Brunost (feel free to make it with any cheese) To make the meatloaf, get some lean ground beef and follow this recipe to make it: https://northwildkitchen.com/brown-cheese-meatloaf-kjottpudding-med-brunost/ To make the mashed potato sauce: 1. Boil and mash or rice the potatoes. 2. Warm some milk (this time I used goat milk), grate more Brunost and dissolve it in the milk together with a bit of salt. 3. Mix well with the potatoes. 4. When the meatloaf was baking, it probably released some juice. Pour that in the potato mash and mix again. The final consistency should resemble a thick, creamy sauce with a lot of cheese and meat flavour. If you make it the way I did (250 grams of potatoes, 120 ml of milk, 50 grams of cheese and about 50 ml of meat juice), you should be able to pour it with a spoon. 646 calories and 58 grams of protein (meatloaf only)

Put the crepe on a plate, fill with goat quark or soft goat cheese and Italian mostarda - I used one made with grapes, apples, pears, hazelnuts and walnuts (no added sugar).
