Side chest. Legs: - Front leg closer to the camera. - Knees bent to appear shorter and wider. - Push the thighs against each other to make them wider. - Lift the heel of the back leg to flex the calf. Torso: - Rotate the upper torso towards the camera while rotating the waist in the opposite direction, since it looks the narrowest from the side. - Do a vacuum. - Push the chest up. Arms: - Push the back shoulder forward to show both arms. Also, use it to squeeze your chest from the outside. - Hands down to your waist to show the ribs. - Front elbow back to appear wider and flex the front arm biceps at the same time. - Lift the whole upper torso up to flex the traps.

Front double biceps. Legs: - Knees slightly bent, don't try to hyperextend your legs. You'll look shorter and wider. - Feet facing out with 60 to 90 degree angle between them. That shows the inner side of your thighs. - Push the feet into the ground and flex the quads as if you wanted to slide them forward. Imagine there's a sheet of paper on the ground and you want to move it by stepping on it and sliding it forward. Torso: - Push your hips back, which stretches your waist and makes it look longer. - Do a vacuum. Pull the abs back and up in a J trajectory inside your rib cage. - Push the chest up and squeeze it from the outside. - Spread the lats wide. Arms: - Elbows above your shoulders. - Fists between your delts and biceps, below the top of your head but above your ears.

Coffee has been in wide consumption ever since the 15th century, it is one of the most popular drinks on the planet and undoubtedly an incredibly potent performance enhancer. Yet in spite of all this, there are still common misconceptions about this drink and its potency and safety. There are many products which are marketed as potent nootropics, performance enhancers and superfoods but none of them come close to coffee.

You may already know I drink a lot of coffee. Here are some reasons why. With that being said; Coffee is made with exactly two ingredients: 1. Ground coffee beans 2. Hot (not boiling) water No sugar, no milk, no syrup, no butter, etc. - if it contains more than two ingredients, it‚Äôs not coffee, it‚Äôs a mixed drink. Just like a Mojito is not rum or a Lynchburg Lemonade is not whiskey, a Pumpkin Spice Latte is not coffee.

Pumpkin pancake: 1. Roast a pumpkin in the oven. 2. Peel it. 3. Put it in a blender, add egg, milk, flour and spices if you want to (I used cinnamon and ginger). 4. Melt a small bit of butter on a pan. 5. Cook the pancake from one side until it easily separates from the pan, then flip and cook from the other side. You will need to experiment with the exact ratio of flour and other ingredients because without enough gluten in the batter, you'll end up with scrambled pumpkin puree. Eat the pancake as it is or fill it with something. 222 calories and 10 grams of protein including the creme fraiche and pumpkin seed oil topping.

I hate to break it to you, but you are being judged all the time. Even worse, you are judging people all the time, whether you are aware of that or not. People are by default judgmental, but this isn‚Äôt some sort of a problem that we need to overcome, it‚Äôs just an evolutionary reflex. Therefore since we cannot change the fact that we will be judged and branded based on our looks, we might as well acknowledge that as a reality and present ourselves appropriately. Whatever appropriate means to us personally. After all, the dumbest decision one could make is to let others do the branding in his name. If you want to be taken seriously, look serious. And if you want to be treated like a pleb, look like a pleb. It is that simple.

This. I keep saying it all the time and I‚Äôm happy to see that so do other people. What you look like matters. Both your physique and your clothes and overall appearance. And if there‚Äôs one thing I think has to be stressed then it‚Äôs this: Wear clothes that fit. No matter whether you‚Äôre tall, short, skinny, fat, you‚Äôll always look better in properly fitting clothes. I also want you to pay attention to the list of ingredients in the recipe above. Every single one is completely natural; bananas grow on a tree, curd cheese is made from milk, salt comes from the sea, and spices are just seeds of plants. Yet there are so many flavours that without listing them, you'd probably have a difficult time trying to figure out what you're tasting. And that's the style of cooking I prefer. I ate ze bugs (and wouldn‚Äôt mind doing it again). I will get straight to the point: I wish people were as concerned about all the food they eat and all the ingredients in it as they are about ‚Äúze bugs‚Äù, since it sounds really bizarre when someone who has no issue with drinking a six-pack of beer and then eating a pile of junk food is freaking out about the idea of eating a dried cricket. Seriously; when we for a moment disregard who‚Äôs promoting this idea and the whole ideological conflict associated with it, what exactly is supposed to be the problem? First of all, companies can only put their products in the shops; they can‚Äôt put it in your basket or in your mouth, just like they can‚Äôt make you drink beer or eat junk food (yet most people keep doing it for whatever reason). Second, let‚Äôs say you‚Äôd eat some insects; what exactly you imagine would happen or what exactly is supposed to be the problem? It certainly wasn‚Äôt the worst thing I‚Äôve ever eaten and it certainly wouldn‚Äôt be any different in your case. When I look at the relatively recent (d)evolution of the Western diet, I dare say that from the nutritional perspective, insects look better than 90% of ingredients that have been added to people‚Äôs food since 1945. Yet I rarely see people protesting against the consumption of Nutella, McDonald‚Äôs or Coca-Cola. Possibly the best illustration of what I‚Äôm talking about was an image, where the author complained that there was cricket flour in a bag of something called ‚ÄúCheddar Cheese Puffs‚Äù. I mean ‚Äì if you bought something the manufacturer described as ‚ÄúPuffs‚Äù, what the fuck are you expecting to find in the bag, a block of cheese? I went through the (rather long) list of ingredients and the cricket flour certainly wasn‚Äôt what I would have the biggest issue with. But I guess eating shapes made of various flours and seed oils is OK for some people as long as there are no insects in them. By the way, I had an opportunity to taste an insect protein bar couple years ago in Germany. It tasted‚Ä¶ like nothing. Just like most protein bars. If it hadn‚Äôt been written on the packaging, I would have never guessed that one of the ingredients was a protein powder made of insects. Which isn‚Äôt exactly surprising, given I‚Äôve recently heard about a study, in which people didn‚Äôt notice when 10% of their cereals were replaced with wooden sawdust. The only problem (besides the ideological one) that people have with consuming insects is what they look like. They‚Äôre not furry and fluffy and have too many legs and other body parts that most people can‚Äôt even name so people think eating insects is just gross. But hey - it‚Äôs not like anyone is expecting you to eat a whole insect like a bird. Most people eat chicken and if I told you to eat a whole chicken with the head, legs, feathers etc. you probably wouldn‚Äôt find that idea too appetizing either. And once something gets processed into a powder, what difference does it make, what it originally was? It‚Äôs not like too many people care what kind of protein is in their protein puddings, breads, pancakes, etc. ‚Äì they see the word ‚Äúprotein‚Äù and they buy it, usually for much more than it‚Äôs really worth. So calm down and relax; nobody is forcing you to eat anything and if you want to be particular about what you eat or don‚Äôt eat, there are about 1000 other ingredients that deserve more of your attention than some insects. And don't get me wrong; I am not suggesting that you should replace your meat with insects. Nor am I going to start eating them or include them in my recipes. I am only suggesting to stop being so emotional about the whole subject and approach it like an adult, rational person. P.S. Some food for thought to end this with. Anytime I saw a photo of an insect farm, it was just a smaller version of a farm using battery cages for larger animals. Won‚Äôt it be just a matter of time, before someone starts demanding free-range insects raised on a meadow with flowers, fresh air, natural sunlight etc. which will eventually make them just as expensive as any other animals?

Couple days ago, I watched a documentary about the obesity pandemic. As usually, it blamed the food industry, advertising, fast food, processed foods, sugar, cheap vegetable oils, etc. ‚Äì the usual list of what most people tend to blame for every other person being fat. In a nutshell, it has come to the usual conclusion that we‚Äôre all just poor, innocent victims of the evil, greedy food and advertising industry and that with what‚Äôs being offered to us, we basically don‚Äôt have a choice other than to gain weight and get fat. So I decided to tell you something about a man, whom I‚Äôll call Fat Henry. Fat Henry wasn‚Äôt born fat, just like nobody else was born fat. But he eventually got fat. Very fat, even by modern western standards. When he eventually died at the age of 55 (most likely as a direct consequence of his obesity), he was weighing close to 400 lbs and his waist measuring over 52 inches. Fat Henry also suffered from diabetes, high blood pressure, gout, leg ulcers and poor eyesight, among other problems, which we commonly refer to as ‚Äúdiseases of civilization‚Äù and associate with modern diet rich in processes foods, seed oils and refined sugar. However, Fat Henry‚Äôs diet was nothing like that. Fat Henry ate mostly organic, free-range, grass-fed meat, fish, eggs, bread and pastry and fresh or preserved fruit, although he did drink a lot of beer and wine. However, he did not consume any industrially processed food, any seed oils, any soy and very little sugar. And how can we be so sure he didn‚Äôt? Fat Henry‚Äôs full name was Henry Tudor, also known as Henry VIII. He was the King of England and lived between 1491 and 1547. Therefore, he couldn‚Äôt have consumed any industrially processed food because there was no food (or any) industry to start with. He couldn‚Äôt have consumed any seed oils because their extraction from seeds was not invented yet, he couldn‚Äôt have consumed soy because it wasn‚Äôt available in Europe until some 200 years later and he couldn‚Äôt have consumed a lot of sugar because back then England did not have any colonies to grow it so it had to be imported from small Portuguese colonies west of Africa and later from Brazil. The only thing that made Henry fat and eventually killed him was a massive calorie surplus (it‚Äôs estimated he ate about 5000 calories a day), in other words, he just ate too much. That‚Äôs it. Therefore, I want you to stop pointing your fingers in different directions and claiming that this or that is responsible for the obesity pandemic or that all you need to do to lose weight is to introduce this or remove that from your diet. Because it isn‚Äôt. It doesn‚Äôt matter if the chicken you ate was fed with soy, grass, goat milk or absorbed pure Vril energy from the air; if you eat 5000 calories worth of it day after day, you will get fat just like Henry did (unless you have a workout routine of an Olympic athlete and manage to burn 5000 calories a day, but I‚Äôm pretty convinced this does not apply to 99% of people reading this). And don‚Äôt get me wrong, I‚Äôm not trying to tell you that all foods are equal. Surely, some are more likely to cause problems like diabetes than others and if Henry ate at McDonald‚Äôs, maybe he would have died ten years earlier than he did. Eating 5000 calories worth of deer ham is not the same as drinking 5000 calories worth of milk shake. But both will make you fat and therefore if you want to stay lean, you have to have an idea of how much you‚Äôre eating to not get in a long-term calorie surplus and there‚Äôs no way around it. Any influencer who‚Äôs telling you otherwise is bullshitting you.

Semolina pudding reinvented. Semolina pudding is first mentioned in a 4th-century cookbook from the Roman Empire where it was eaten with almonds, raisins and dessert wine but now it's mainly known in Central Europe where it's mostly fed to kids with sugar, melted butter and sweetened alkalised ("Dutch") cocoa. For those unfamiliar with it; it's something between oat porridge and corn polenta, but made with semolina or spelt flour. For my recipe, I used coarsely ground wholegrain spelt flour which gives the dish a richer taste. The flour is soaked in milk for at least an hour. Then, it's slowly cooked over low heat. You must keep stirring it as it cooks, otherwise, it sticks to the bottom of the pot and burns. For 40 grams of flour expect to use at least 250 ml of milk but even as much as 400 ml. Today I used full-fat goat's milk, for a heavier, creamier texture you can try sheep. The recipe continues in the comments...

Some important points about heat: Your muscle convert energy (calories) to movement + heat. If your muscles are close to the skin, the heat is released in the air, as long as the air is colder than your body - that means less than 37 ¬∞C. However, if there‚Äôs a layer of fat between the muscles and the skin, this fat serves as thermal insulation and the heat gets trapped in the fat tissue. That‚Äôs why animals living in polar regions like penguin (30%), seal (40%) or polar bear (50%) have a lot of fat. So if you have let‚Äôs say 1‚Äù of body fat, it‚Äôs like walking around in a 1‚Äù thick winter jacket year round. And if you look at people around you, you can easily tell that many of them carry more than 1‚Äù of such thermal insulation. But that‚Äôs not everything. When your body is too hot, your veins get closer to the skin so that the blood in them can cool down. (That‚Äôs why you look more vascular in summer even with the same body fat percentage, given your body fat percentage is not comparable to a penguin.) However, when there‚Äôs that 1‚Äù of fat between your veins and your skin, this cooling method doesn‚Äôt work and your body has to sweat instead - that‚Äôs why fat people sweat more. Last but not least, just like you can get used to being cold by having cold showers in winter, you can do the opposite and improve your heat tolerance by regularly exposing yourself to heat. Point being; regardless of how much you lift or what your goals are, it‚Äôs objectively better to have lower body fat percentage - at least in summer.

cleaned_message: Lessons learned, not only from Okinawa but also from other ‚ÄúBlue Zones‚Äù: 1. Physical activity increases your life expectancy. 2. Being fat decreases your life expectancy. 3. Industrially processed food decreases your life expectancy. 4. Added sugar decreases your life expectancy. 5. People living in the ‚ÄúBlue Zones‚Äù eat relatively simple, natural, fresh and mostly local ingredients. 6. People living in the ‚ÄúBlue Zones‚Äù, contrary to many popular claims about life expectancy, do not follow any restrictive diet and do not eat anything abnormal. They eat carbs, they eat vegetables, they eat fruit, they eat bread, they eat meat, they eat fish‚Ä¶ they do not drink gallons of raw milk, they do not drink raw eggs, they do not eat beef liver, they do not drink coffee with butter, they do not take twenty different supplements a day‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre getting the point. 7. Saying that - longevity / life expectancy and physical size / strength are not correlated. Okinawa certainly isn‚Äôt the home of the tallest, strongest humans, neither is Ikaria or Sardinia. Quite the opposite; the Okinawans are even shorter than most Japanese and the Sardinians are among the shortest people in Europe. Which implies that food which makes you bigger and stronger doesn‚Äôt necessarily make you live longer (and vice versa), therefore you may have to choose one or the other. More about Blue Zones here: https://www.bluezones.com/

Violet potato gnocchi with steamed salmon and lemon and dill sauce. The potatoes: Apart from their colour, they smell and taste slightly different from normal ones. They smell and taste like ash-roasted potatoes with hints of beetroot. After steaming, they're much denser and you will need some real strength to push them through a potato ricer. The flesh of the potato has various colours, ranging from pale purple-grey to dark indigo / midnight purple. Because of their texture, you will need to use less flour than you normally would. The salmon: I steamed it in lemon-infused water; simply squeeze half of a lemon all over the salmon fillet, then cut the rest and throw it in the water you will steam the salmon in. The sauce: I mixed one part of light creme fraiche and one part of thick Bulgarian sheep yogurt. I added lemon zest, fresh dill and some fresh lemon juice. To reduce the thickness of the sauce, I added some of the lemon-infused water I steamed the salmon in. 430 calories and 30 grams of protein.

When I was a kid, I liked to pretend I was a dinosaur, sometimes. At other times, an Indian, or even a tank. ‚ÄúPeople are who they say they are - I am less concerned with certainty around identity and more concerned with embodiment goals.‚Äù I could‚Äôve had plate armor, a mouth full of huge teeth and a mounted cannon. I feel robbed. In seriousness, this is the kind of madness and mayhem that will be going on with greater frequency and being completely normalized for the next generation. It‚Äôs not about what they can just get away with now - it‚Äôs about what they can keep hammering into hearts and minds until that just seems normal for the youth who become the adults of tomorrow. The way to combat this stuff isn‚Äôt marches, protests, or impotent displays of disagreement. It‚Äôs a complete lifestyle that includes community, culture, education, positive role models, and a sense of meaning, of purpose and belonging. My crew has gotten so much shit over the years from others on ‚Äúthe right‚Äù for not being ‚Äúpolitical‚Äù enough. Meanwhile, I am left to wonder where these other groups have gone. Where their land is. Where their community is centered. Where their children are. Life itself is the revolt. But go hold a sign if you want.

Perfection is impossible to attain, unless, perhaps, one turns their life into a single line of poetry, written with a splash of blood. I‚Äôm still bleeding. Still trying. Still living. And in the recent months, still realizing that politeness and compassion are always going to be good things, but my weaker self doesn‚Äôt need as much compassion from me as I sometimes allow myself to believe. It needs an Iron Fist. And when I feel myself tapping on my own shoulder, saying, ‚Äúcome on. This way,‚Äù and I ignore it‚Ä¶ I need a hammer to the face. That‚Äôs what Operation Werewolf always was to me, and some people got that and resonated. It was an exaggerated version of something, a concept deliberately over the top from its inception in that little notebook, terminologies, aesthetic and all, designed to shatter excuses with a sledgehammer and shake things up, to get The Fire burning. I guess I, for one, still need that. My higher self is still calling from somewhere in space and time, willing my current self to be like him. Maybe that‚Äôs what enlightenment is, after all: Listening to some version of yourself that exists somewhere, someplace, that is the best version of you that will ever be, in any reality, and doing everything you can to line up with that in this one we‚Äôre living in now. I‚Äôm sitting in a tiny cabin in the woods typing this out to myself. But I‚Äôm typing it to you too. Whoever you are, reading this. Maybe you feel like the world is a dark place, and you are alien to it, and uncertain of where to go, or what to do. I‚Äôve felt like that. Maybe you feel, as Hemingway said, that this world is a fine place, and worth fighting for. I feel that, too. Fuck their world, but let‚Äôs not throw the good out with the bad. We should be neither misfits nor miscreants, outcasts or ‚Äúoutlaws,‚Äù save from the world they‚Äôve built without our consent. Instead, we must, as ever, build our own while braving theirs. This can be done, and we will see miracles and radical changes in our own lifetimes. I believe this with every ounce of my burning heart. But in order to do it, we will need three things: Pure hearts. Strong limbs. Actions matching words. Welcome back, or, welcome aboard. Standby for further transmissions. XCII - Paul Waggener, Summer 2022

There was always going to be a return to this thing. In some form or another, for me, it was inevitable. For as many bad things as it created or were done in its name, it was always the source of expression I resonated with the most of anything I‚Äôd ever worked on. This was because I did my best to communicate with myself. I was unconcerned with ‚Äúmaximal reach.‚Äù There were specific things done, and set into place to ensure, from the beginning, that it wouldn‚Äôt be something that was able to have a broad reach. I was looking to reach myself. That is, I was looking to touch that part of myself that was the self I always had wanted to be, to aspire to, and ultimately, upon attaining, realize that I had only reached another false summit. On my best days, I felt like my writing didn‚Äôt even come from the ‚Äúme‚Äù that was sitting at the table pounding away on the keys - rather, it seemed to me when I really ‚Äúnailed‚Äù it, that it was some future version of myself speaking back through time‚Ä¶ Extending a hand to the ‚Äúme‚Äù that existed now, saying ‚ÄúThis way. I can help you get there.‚Äù Ultimately, what created a necessary long ‚Äúcessation‚Äù of above ground, publicly accessible transmissions, was what I saw being done ‚Äúunder the banner‚Äù of OPWW, so to speak. Morons, cop-magnets, real cops, and ultimately people not interested in evolving and moving forward as human beings but remaining mired only in the ‚Äútrappings‚Äù of the project, that is to say, only the exterior ‚Äúhard signal‚Äù aesthetic. I won‚Äôt judge them too harshly - after all, it was my creation. But I would watch, from some cave on the coastal rocks of the Northwest, from an ancient cobbled street in old Europe, from the back of a bar in Appalachia, from the edge of the fire in the dark woods, and I would see: None of them. The real quality of the Operation was what it brought out during difficult to attend and difficult to participate in events, and moreso, lifestyle. I found friendships and brotherhood that exist to this day from those years, with individuals from quite literally, around the globe. Men of action, men of honor, men of worth. Trappings don‚Äôt mean shit. A porno mag can be stuck inside a copy of the Gutenberg Bible, and it‚Äôs still just vile smut. Tee shirts, tattoos, slogans, all the rest- it didn‚Äôt matter whether I had created them or not‚Ä¶it was how I saw them used over and over again that disheartened me and made me step back in order to find a solution. The solution was: See who was still there when the dust settled, and who was miraculously long gone. Whose lives looked the same after they discovered Werewolf, and after Werewolf was ‚Äúover?‚Äù Who understood well enough the appellation itself, and all that implied, so eloquently put into song by friends of ‚Äúour thing,‚Äù black metal titans Marduk: ‚ÄúWerewolf riding the end times Werewolf behind enemy lines‚Ä¶‚Äù So, I did just that. I watched and I kept contact with those who kept contact with me. Those still ‚Äúliving it.‚Äù It was few enough compared to the hundreds or thousands who had claimed some kind of ‚Äúassociation,‚Äù but it was men I had bled and sweated with across the face of the earth, and I had no interest in abandoning those connections, and never did. We kept talking. Our crews stayed training, working together to build a good life among the ruins of the modern world. I used the time to broaden my experience, and my horizons. I increased my skill, widened my network, elevated my leverage. All the time, I was doing the things that I said I would do when I began Operation Werewolf in that little beat up black notebook that I still keep like a holy relic: ‚ÄúOperation Werewolf is rabid fucking resistance,‚Äù it began, as it delivered to me an edict from my higher self of how my life would be lived. I did not attain perfection adhering to that edict. I let myself down many times. But the Operation, as many of us have often said, is ongoing.

Today's dinner: carbonara. This one is normally a heavy dish full of fat but at the same time, the Italians tend to be very particular when it comes to the ingredients used, therefore I had to carefully consider every single ingredient. Once again, I used Le Rustichelle pasta, which connected with the cream very well and was certainly worth the high price. The meat is low-fat unsmoked bacon, I did not use smoked one to not alter the taste too much. I know that the recipe asks for Guanciale, but it has simply too much fat and not enough protein at the same time. I used a whole egg like people originally did, and Pecorino Romano cheese. There's also a pinch of black pepper and that's it. As photographed, the meal contains 484 calories and 44 grams of protein.

Pappa al Pomodoro with a few extra ingredients. The recipe is originally a tomato and bread soup but with added meat, it is a quicker and cheaper alternative to pasta because you can make it with dry / leftover bread (I used sliced toast bread I got for sale for 30 cents - in contrast to that, a comparable amount of artisan Italian pasta can cost up to 10 EUR). Ingredients: white onion, canned tomatoes, olive oil, canned tuna, black olives, Pecorino Romano cheese, salt, pepper and fresh basil. Preparation: chop and saute the onion in some olive oil (some, not five tablespoons, you're not meant to deep-fry it), add the rest of the ingredients and cook over low heat for a few minutes. 670 calories and 56 grams of protein.

It's asparagus season so here's a new recipe: creamy white asparagus soup. Saute one large onion on a few grams of smoked or normal butter. Move it into a pot, add about 500 grams of chopped asparagus and cover with vegetable stock. Add salt and cook for about 15 to 20 minutes. In a bowl, mix 100 grams of skyr, 50 grams of creme fraiche and horseradish. Season with black pepper and nutmeg. Meanwhile, brown some lean bacon on a pan. When the soup is cooked, add the dairy into the pot and blend everything with a blender. Chop the bacon and add it to the bowl. Serve as it is or with some toasted bread. One pot of the soup has 320 calories and 42 grams of protein. Bonus fact: asparagus is a diuretic so if you want to lower your weight by getting rid of some water, this is the food to eat.

Lads, chances are you don‚Äôt need to take 25 different supplements every day. After all, the original role of supplements was to supplement (that is, add on top) a certain nutrient/macro/micro that you are missing out on. Therefore most supplements don‚Äôt do anything spectacular, no matter how outwardly the marketing is. Chances are you don‚Äôt need that extra pill, and chances are that extra pill won‚Äôt do anything outside of making you waste your money, because at the end of the day that is what most supplements do nowadays, waste your money. In this first part I went into the most popular bodybuilding/strength training supplements including protein powder, creatine, preworkouts, BCAA‚Äôs and testosterone boosters, explained how they work and if they are worth the money or not. I plan on covering more in the future, especially the ones there is a lot of debate currently, including but not limited to: fish oil, zinc, vitamin C etc. If you have any specific supplement requests feel free to let me know.

I told you‚Ä¶ (As for pre-workouts, from my point of view, most of them are nothing but disgusting and overpriced caffeine diluted in a blend of other random chemicals, most of which have no other than placebo effect.)

Green borscht. This is the first time I have cooked a Ukrainian meal before eating one cooked by someone from there. The ingredients I decided to use are turkey broth, turkey meat, potatoes, onion, sorrel, dill, eggs and creme fraiche. The primary ingredient is sorrel, which is a sour-tasting plant/herb full of vitamin A, C and potassium. Two bowls of this soup, made with 150 grams of turkey, 150 grams of potatoes and two eggs, contain 470 calories and 50 grams of protein.

A comment on so-called ‚Äúhealthy‚Äù foods: Food per se isn‚Äôt healthy or unhealthy. You are. Food cannot end up in a hospital. You can. In other words, whether food is healthy or unhealthy only depends on what you want to happen with your body vs. what that food does to it. Is peanut butter healthy? Well, it depends on whether your BMI is 20 and you‚Äôre trying to bulk, your BMI is 30 and you‚Äôre trying to cut or you‚Äôre allergic to peanuts. Stop paying attention to what other people or companies label as ‚Äúhealthy‚Äù (speaking from experience, it can be just about everything) and start paying attention to what nutrients you need. Last but not least: Being fat is always unhealthy. Therefore, any food that makes you fat or is preventing you from losing that fat is unhealthy, no matter what it is and where it came from. There may be numerous benefits of consuming stuff like raw milk, olive oil, nuts and whatnot but if I‚Äôm trying to cut, I‚Äôm going to avoid them and re-introduce them to my diet later.

Stuffed peppers. "Like grandma's, but healthier." Hungarian wax peppers stuffed with ground chicken, mozzarella, egg, red paprika and fresh parsley. 115 calories and 13 grams of protein per one pepper including the tomato sauce in which the peppers are cooked (full recipe in my cookbook).

A combination of two recipes from Vicenzo's Plate that I tried today: polenta and meatballs in tomato sauce. This meal takes less than 10 minutes to prepare; the polenta cooks in about 3-4 minutes (you may want to add some water depending on how thick you want it to be) and then add some tomato passata and a bit of grated pecorino cheese. The meatballs are made by mixing ground chicken (or other meat) with egg, grated/shredded mozzarella cheese and some fresh finely chopped parsley. If you make them small enough (I'd compare their size to grapes), they cook in boiling water in about 2 minutes. The meal made with 40 grams of polenta and 100 grams of chicken has 380 calories and 30 grams of protein.

Cocoa and peanut butter crepes. Crepes are normally made with egg, milk and flour but you can mix the flour with other dry ingredients (except sugar and sweeteners because these are forbidden). Here I mixed one part wholegrain flour, one part low-fat cocoa powder and one part peanut butter powder. 320 calories and 35 grams of protein including the curd cheese and walnuts.

Snert Salad This dish doesn't have a name but I decided to call it Snert Salad because it's nearly identical to the Dutch Snert soup. Cook the soup (I used split peas, potato, carrot and celery) until all the water has either evaporated or has been absorbed by the vegetables. Mix with slow-cooked / pulled beef or pork and as a dressing, use a bit of creamed horseradish and grated Gouda or similar cheese. 450 calories and 40 grams of protein.

Glorious regiment "Azov" - 8 years! May 5 marks the 8th anniversary of the founding of the legendary Ukrainian unit - the Azov Regiment. Dill sauce (typically served with beef, eggs, potatoes or dumplings) is a true Czech classic, however, the way it's originally prepared (with butter, flour and heavy cream) it adds a substantial number of calories to your plate. Therefore I made a lighter version based on the Armenian spas yoghurt soup. To cook it, mix some beef broth, one egg, one Greek yoghurt, some creme fraiche, wholegrain mustard and dill and cook for a few minutes just to make the flavours blend. If you want to make it thicker, either reduce the broth first or mash one small potato and mix it with the sauce. Here served with boiled potatoes and slow-cooked beef, but it also pairs well with salmon. 208 calories and 20 grams of protein in the sauce, 531 calories and 54 grams of protein including the potatoes and beef (150 grams each).

Ukrainian borscht. This dish has one undeniable advantage; since there's no official recipe (every household cooks it differently) it allows you to get creative with ingredients. I made it with beetroot, cabbage, potato, carrot, onion, a bit of horseradish, parsley, dill, beef stock and a lot of beef. A full pot of the soup, which is about 2.5 litres or 10 US cups has about 400 calories (minus the beef). I prefer to cook the meat separately, so that I know (and can control) how much meat I'll have in one serving. Reminder: beetroot is a source of nitrogen, which gives your muscles a good pump, therefore it's good pre-workout food.

Chicken Cacciatore. A few weeks ago I started following https://www.vincenzosplate.com/ on YouTube and this is the first recipe I decided to recreate. It's reasonably healthy as it is so I did not change any of the ingredients, I only opted for leaner chicken meat (a mix of breasts and thighs) and I used half a tablespoon (7 grams) of olive oil rather than three - after all, I needed to brown the chicken, not deep-fry it. That step alone reduced the number of calories by almost 300. A full pot made of almost 1 kg of chicken has 1200 calories and 200 grams of protein. You can eat it as it is, with some bread or with fresh polenta - I like the last idea because it thickens the sauce. Ingredients and preparation in the comments.

In medieval Europe when people weren't stuffing themselves with sugar because it simply wasn't available, carrots, which contain about 5% to 6% natural sugar, were used in cooking as a sweetener. Today, most people wouldn't describe them as sweet simply because after decades of overloading their taste buds with sugar and sweeteners they desensitized them and now don't consider food sweet unless there's >30% sugar in it. It's the same as people from tropical countries describing European food as bland and tasteless because it's not covered with chilli, curry or some other spice. However, by systematically eliminating sugar and sweeteners(!) from your diet, you can once again start enjoying the natural sweetness of carrots and other foods. Another breakfast idea; sardines spread with capers and lemon. This one is a perfect example of why I wrote my cookbook. Living in a landlocked country on the eastern side of the Iron Curtain, my parents didn't have access to any fresh saltwater fish. However, every grocery store sold canned "Baltic Sardines" (in fact European Sprats, since Sardines don't live in the Baltic Sea) imported from the Soviet Union (as you can see, communists are willing to lie about absolutely anything, including canned fish). So they used to make this cheap parody of a French/Portuguese sardine pate, made of canned sprats, margarine (yes, margarine), mustard and onion. As you can imagine, it was everything but healthy, so once I started buying my own food, I stopped eating them. Until recently, when I made some research and modified the recipe. Ingredients: 1. Can of sardines (about 60-65 grams) 2. Equal amount of Icelandic skyr 3. Half the amount or 30 grams of light creme fraiche 4. Capers 5. Lemon juice and lemon zest

James Cook was one of the first ship captains to recognize that a lack of Vitamin C in a sailor's diet (due mostly to a lack of fresh fruit and vegetables) caused scurvy, a terrible disease that killed millions of sailors in those times. While fresh fruit and vegetables weren‚Äôt available on ships unless they landed, he found out that the nutrient-rich pickled cabbage seemed to keep the disease at bay. Therefore, Captain Cook always sailed with barrels of fermented cabbage (7,860 pounds of sauerkraut, to be exact) which he insisted the sailors eat. This way Cook managed to keep all three of his expeditions nearly scurvy-free. His only problem was getting his crew to eat it. To trick them, Cook simply had sauerkraut ‚Äúdressed every day‚Äù for the officers‚Äô table. When the enlisted men saw their superiors eating it, they assumed it was a delicacy and requested some for themselves.

Curd cheese pancakes (a classic, recipe in my cookbook) with homemade pear sauce. Ingredients for the sauce: A large, soft, watery pear Water Earl grey tea Almond flour (ground almonds) Tonka beans Vanilla Chicory root syrup How to prepare it: 1. In a steamer, steam the pears in water with tea leaves for about 20-30 minutes. This will turn the water into tea, which will soak into the pears. 2. Transfer the pears into a blender, add some almond flour (makes the sauce thicker) and tea (makes the sauce more watery). 3. Blend, then add tonka beans and vanilla and mix. 4. Add the chicory root syrup to taste (depending on how strong the tea was). The syrup is mostly fibre and only 5% sugar but has a caramel-like taste. The sauce is very aromatic and smells more like a Guerlain perfume than anything you'd buy from a grocery store.

Tafelspitz - The Emperor's Favourite One of Austria's most popular dishes is relatively light and simple - but its preparation is anything but that. 1. Boil veal or beef in salt water. You can add beef bones if you want to. 2. For the last 30 minutes, add carrot, parsley and fresh chives. 3. In a separate pot, boil some potatoes. Alternatively, you can steam the potatoes and vegetables together. 4. Once the potatoes are cooked, rice or mash them, add some salt and roast on a pan. 5. First side - apple and horseradish. Peel an apple and decide if you want to cook it or use it raw. Then blend it with fresh horseradish in a blender. 6. Second side - creamed spinach. Boil fresh spinach leaves for about a minute, then squeeze all the water out. Add some sour cream and blend in a blender. 7. Third side - chive sauce. Boil an egg, then peel it. Add equal parts of white skyr or Greek yoghurt and sour cream. Blend in a blender. Chop some fresh chives and mix them with the sauce. Add a few drops of lemon juice.

Spas. The soup, not the shotgun. I have never visited Armenia or eaten this soup, but I recently saw it on the menu of a local Armenian restaurant and decided to re-create it. 1. Cook 100 grams of wheat berries for about 40 minutes or until reasonably soft (their texture should resemble corn rather than rice or pasta). 2. Mix 400 grams of low-fat Greek yoghurt, 100 grams of light creme fraiche or sour cream, 1 egg and 25 grams of flour. 3. Add about 400 to 500 ml of chicken (or other) broth or water. 4. Add the cooked wheat berries and cook over medium heat for another 20 minutes. 5. Roast some green onions (the white parts) on a pan. 6. Add them to the soup. Add some fresh coriander and some lemon juice. Can be eaten as it is or with some meat. A full pot of the soup including the wheat berries, without meat, has 866 calories and 58 grams of protein. "There are two types of fat burners: ineffective and illegal." You may have read this sentence in the past, but today I decided to look at the numbers to put things in perspective and give you a better idea of how do commercially available fat burners compare to those that are either prescription-only or completely banned. First of all, we need to draw a line between stimulants and fat burners. Stimulants (all kinds of pre-workout blends, energy drinks, etc.) make you feel less tired and give you more energy to work out. That's all. Sugar is a stimulant too, but nobody would call it a fat burner for obvious reasons. To classify as a fat burner, a substance should increase your basal metabolic rate (BMR). That means your body burns more energy even when doing nothing (in contrast to stimulants where you only burn extra calories during a workout). The main supplement in almost every fat burner is caffeine. Caffeine is technically a fat burner. According to various studies, 100 mg of caffeine boosts one's BMR by about 3% to 4%. Not great, not terrible. So where's the catch? Well; it only does so for about 2.5 hours after its consumption. This means that to have an increased BMR all day long, you would need to take it ten times a day. And while I know many coffee lovers, I don't think anyone loves it enough to wake up twice a night to drink one. Let's say you don't want to do it that often. How many calories will you burn after one such dose? If your normal BMR is 2500 calories in 24 hours, a 4% increase over the course of 2.5 hours translates to burning extra 10 calories. That's what a person burns during two minutes or 160 metres of walking. You could walk around your house while waiting for that coffee to brew and you would burn more calories. Now let's look at one of the most popular fat burning PEDs: Clenbuterol. Clenbuterol boosts one's BMR by about 20% (it's 5x stronger than caffeine) but what's more important, its half-life in the human body is about 35 hours. This means you can take it once and you'll burn extra 500 calories a day, given the same BMR. To put this to perspective: you would need to consume about 5 grams of caffeine (10x what's considered a safe daily intake), which equals about 400 grams of coffee beans (almost two bags). Given the price of caffeine, it would cost you about $40 a month (that's if you bought pure caffeine, not coffee beans) in contrast to about $10, which is the cost of a month's worth of genuine Clenbuterol. Why am I sharing all this? It's entirely up to you to decide what to take or not, I am not encouraging anyone to take any particular substance. However, you should know that commercially available fat burners, pre-workouts and other dietary supplements are an utter waste of money, especially considering their price-to-performance ratio, which is one of the two main reasons why I don't take them (the other one is the fact that their taste is just vile). Save yourself the money and spend it on... better food or whatever.

Physique Friday. Saying that; every Friday I see so many photos that aren't anything but lazy snapshots. Nobody says you need to be a professional photographer or have a fully equipped studio at home. But these photos are meant to make an impression. So make them show you in the best light (pun intended), not as someone who's lazy and simply doesn't care. It's no different from being dirty or badly dressed - it's a sign of disrespect towards yourself as well as the others. It tells them "you weren't worth more than 10 seconds of my time". Make your physique photoshoots a special occasion; something you look forward to. Don't approach it as a chore that you do just for the sake of being able to say that you've done it. It's not different from lifting weights or preparing your meals. If you do something, you may as well do it properly. Especially if you only do it once a week.

cleaned_message: ‚ÄúFAKE IT UNTIL THEY MAKE IT‚Äù In the past three weeks I joined a few debates about diets and influencers and noticing the same kind of arguments on several independent occasions I decided to write down my own thoughts on it. Modern-day Internet, and especially social media, are more than anything else a battleground on which millions of individuals and brands fight for others‚Äô attention. The amount of content available increases, but people‚Äôs time to consume it does not. This forces the participants to do more and more extreme things to a) outperform themselves and b) outperform others to offer something nobody has seen before. And while there is nothing wrong with people pushing their limits, try to think what happens when they‚Äôre simply not capable of going any further or never knew anything valuable to start with. You see; not everything you come across on the Internet is real. Actually, most of it probably isn‚Äôt. You have all heard of fake nattys who claimed to have a natural physique while secretly taking steroids and other PEDs. You have probably all heard of influencers and celebrities lifting fake weights to appear stronger than they are. You have seen models Photoshopping their faces and bodies to look better. You have all seen professional athletes promoting supplements that they didn't take for no reason other than the fact that they were sponsored by the brand and paid to do it. You have also probably heard of trends such as ‚ÄúTide pod challenge" or "cinnamon challenge‚Äù when people were consuming substances and objects that ranged from unpleasant to outright harmful. Why? All for the sake of attention. Now add all these and ask yourself a question: Why couldn‚Äôt diets be fake? Why couldn‚Äôt people claim to be on some kind of extreme diet either to simply show off, to sell them a diet plan or supplement or simply to see how many people will copy them? As I mentioned before; we have all heard of fake nattys, I have personally heard of both fake vegans and fake carnivores so why is it so difficult to imagine that just because someone on the Internet claimed to eat this or that doesn‚Äôt mean that he really eats it? People‚Äôs social media profiles don‚Äôt show who they are but rather who they want to be or who they want you to believe they are. Especially when they (can) profit from it. The solution to this problem is called Sagan Standard, which says: "Extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence." The more a person‚Äôs approach differs from what others are doing, the more carefully you should examine it before you decide to follow it. If someone tells you to eat chicken soup and you know that most bodybuilders eat chicken, it‚Äôs safe to assume that it‚Äôs going to be beneficial. If someone tells you to eat a 2-year-old egg and you can‚Äôt think of one more person who does that, it‚Äôs reasonable to stop and ask yourself ‚ÄúIf this is beneficial, why doesn‚Äôt anyone else do it? Who is more likely to be wrong; everyone else or this one guy?‚Äù The answer is usually obvious‚Ä¶

In the second photo, there's a beetroot risotto with turkey. You start with (slow) cooking turkey meat in nothing but salted water, which will turn into a broth. Then take one small beetroot and steam it or bake it in the oven. Now you have all the ingredients ready and you can start preparing the risotto: 1. Finely slice half a banana shallot or red onion. 2. Soften it on a pan with a bit of butter and olive oil. 3. Add the rice and mix with the shallot. 4. Pour in some red wine, mix everything and wait until the wine evaporates. 5. Peel the beetroot and grate it on a cheese grater. 6. Put all the ingredients into a steamer and pour in some red wine and turkey broth. The ratio of rice and liquids (wine+broth) should be 1 to 2.5. 7. Once the water in the steamer starts to boil, turn the heat down and steam for 18 minutes. 8. Add in the turkey, some grated cheese and you can also add some light creme fraiche to make it creamier.

Risotto x 2 Chicken and rice or fish and rice are combinations that are well-known to every bodybuilder, and while they have a reputation of being light and healthy, they also have a reputation of being rather boring. A possible solution is exchanging plain rice for risotto, which has a nicer texture and binds well with other ingredients - you don't need to use more than one or two. In the first photo, there's a fennel and tuna risotto, which is really simple: 1. In a blender or chopper, chop half of a white onion with half of a fennel bulb. 2. Soften them on a pan with some butter and olive oil - you can use the oil from tuna. 3. Add the rice and mix it. 4. Transfer to a steamer and pour 2.5 ml of water for each gram of rice. 5. Steam for 18 minutes, then add some grated cheese, tuna and the green fennel leaves.

Bodybuilding is often used as a synonym for muscle building. But there's more to your body than just muscle mass. You have your brain, your heart, your lungs, your digestive system, your immune system... build it all. Don't build a pile of muscle that can lift a perfectly calibrated bar inside an air-conditioned gym but nothing else. It's a good start, but it shouldn't be the end. It's not enough. Lift in the morning, lift in the evening, lift at night, lift when it's cold, lift when it's hot, lift in different clothes, lift weirdly shaped objects. Do cardio. Ride a bike, go for a hike, climb rocks, train some martial arts. Try new things to get out of your comfort zone. People like to say that you should listen to your body. No. Your body should listen to you. It should do what you want it to do. Call it more than muscle, muscle and fitness, functional bodybuilding, whatever you like, the point is the same; build a body that looks and works the way you want it to. I rode this very bike for 200 km in one day in 30+ degree heat. I climbed a mountain in waist-deep snow. I went on a hike after sleeping for 2.5 hours. I lifted weights in a Mexican gym without air conditioning. I walked a 160 km long forest trail in mid-October. And that's why going for a bike ride five days after being diagnosed with Covid feels like no big deal. Stop muscle building. Start body building.

WHY IT'S BETTER TO BE SHREDDED REGARDLESS OF HOW MUCH YOU'RE LIFTING https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.10.24.465626v1 "SARS-CoV-2 infects human adipose tissue and elicits an inflammatory response consistent with severe COVID-19" Important parts: "Here, we report that SARS-CoV-2 infects human adipose tissue in COVID-19 patients and in vitro. Significantly extending a prior report that human adipocytes can be infected in vitro (15), we identify both tissue-resident macrophages and mature adipocytes as target cells for SARS-CoV-2 infection (16, 17, 19). Additionally, this study reveals that in vitro infection leads to activation of inflammatory pathways in macrophage and preadipocytes and the secretion of inflammatory factors associated with severe COVID-19. Finally, we provide the first evidence that this may be relevant to disease pathogenesis in humans in vivo, as we detected SARS-CoV-2 RNA in VAT, EAT, and SAT of COVID-19 autopsies. We also demonstrate histologic evidence of inflammation adjacent to viral signals in adipose tissue in an autopsy sample. Together, this in-depth analysis of adipose susceptibility and inflammatory response to SARS-CoV-2 infection suggests that adipose tissue may serve as a potential reservoir for SARS-CoV-2 and potentiator of systemic and regional inflammation, possibly contributing to severe clinical disease in obese individuals infected with SARS-CoV-2." "Importantly, infection of adipose tissue drives an inflammatory response in infected macrophages and preadipocytes. Thus, multiple cells within adipose tissue likely participate in both viral replication and inflammation. Importantly, we demonstrated infection and inflammation in adipose tissue adjacent to critical organs such as the heart and intestine, thus pointing to the potential for adipose tissue potentiation of organ damage in severe COVID-19. Furthermore, if adipose cells constitute a reservoir for viral infection, obesity may contribute not only to severe acute disease, but also to long-COVID syndrome. Collectively, our data implies that infection in adipose tissue may partially explain the link between obesity and severe COVID-19." To sum it up: 1. The more fat you have, the more virus you accumulate in your body. 2. The more virus you accumulate, the more severe infection it will cause, especially if the fat the virus is stored in is close to your vital organs (that means around your torso). 3. url_title: SARS-CoV-2 infects human adipose tissue and elicits an inflammatory response consistent with severe COVID-19
url_description: The COVID-19 pandemic, caused by the viral pathogen SARS-CoV-2, has taken the lives of millions of individuals around the world. Obesity is associated with adverse COVID-19 outcomes, but the underlying mechanism is unknown. In this report, we demonstrate that human adipose tissue from multiple depots is permissive to SARS-CoV-2 infection and that infection elicits an inflammatory response, including the secretion of known inflammatory mediators of severe COVID-19. We identify two cellular targets of SARS-CoV-2 infection in adipose tissue: mature adipocytes and adipose tissue macrophages. Adipose tissue macrophage infection is largely restricted to a highly inflammatory subpopulation of macrophages, present at baseline, that is further activated in response to SARS-CoV-2 infection. Preadipocytes, while not infected, adopt a proinflammatory phenotype. An Open Letter to NJP Supporters: Where do I even begin? I guess I'd like to start by saying this is coming from a place of sincerity. Seeing as White Nationalism is poisoned by irony, hyper combvativeness, and catty passive aggressiveness. If you were a supporter or a volunteer for the NJP, I'm sorry. I truly am. You worked hard and risked a lot, and some of you lost a lot. Be it time, money, reputation, a job, what have you. The one consistent thing I see among the former supporters of the NJP is that they all lost trust. And that is the most devastating. I don't need to tell you we as a collective are under attack. What just happened has ensured that good people, people who are willing to give time, money, and show their face in public, will never touch our politics again. Those qualities are rare and so desperately needed for our struggle, especially in the next few years. I'm reminded of 2017. After Charlottesville (who had many of the same organizers oddly enough), everyone had essentially stepped back from demonstrations or even meeting in real life at all. We quarantined online and poisoned ourselves with infighting and garbage like "internet bloodsports."" That isn't the worst part though. Three years after 2017, we got a year of terror. BLM burned our cities, and ZOG used the precarity of capital to force a vaccine on millions of people. And where was our response? There was some pushback from the proud boys when they weren't completely zogged. But OUR response was nowhere to be found. Oh wow, look at the time, another election year right around the corner! And it feels like we are all in this same spot again. We are disorganized, nobody trusts each other, and everyone just wants to retreat into chat rooms on telegram. For those who weren't supporters, you may feel the impulse to attack and jump on NJP supporters. "Yeah, that's what you get for trusting a bunch of podcasters!" "That's what you get for isolating yourself from everyone!" I get it. Being vindicated feels nice, but these people are just like you. They are antagonistic to jewish power, and they care for about the future of their race. They just hitched themselves to the wrong cart. We should be willing to forgive them for that. It's not as if many of us haven't been a part of now defunk organizations. If you were a volunteer for the NJP, we need you. Your people need you. You might not be right for our group, but we can still forward you to someone who might be a fit for you. We need strong men. We need men with work ethic. We need men with courage. I know you guys invested a lot, especially in Ohio. It couldn't have gotten as far as it did without you guys. Please contact us, let's let by gones be by gones, and work together. One of the club's objectives is to fill its ranks with quality members or make quality members out of them. This is why your recruitment tactics and club aesthetics are crucial because what you put out is what you will attract. I have often seen new clubs start looking to go as extreme as possible to garner as much attention as possible. Doing this usually seems to bring guys that are attention seekers or have more of an anti-social background. The problem when your club does this approach to be as edgy as possible is first for recruitment you will only ever get guys that are already into this shock and awe style which many times leaves guys burnt out of chasing the "high" from getting first coverage of the group and then having to constantly be edgier and edgier as they try to get back that "high" (such as what happened to national action). When your club is just starting, the main task should be laying down the groundwork and building a tight-knit club that will be able to weather future storms. Having serious attention on your club will only make things much harder, and if law enforcement is involved, it can halt everything. For example, on my travels across Europe, I stayed in one country for a few months. The local nationalists were not so organized and scattered across different football clubs, bars, and gyms, there was nothing cohesive but there was plenty of potential . So they formed a club within a week. They got around 50 guys. Instead of having some training or hikes, etc., to get to know one another better or discuss tactics and bring in more people silently growing the ranks, they wanted to announce their new club with a bang. The first night they get all 50 guys together, and go to an Antifa bar and graffiti all over smash out the windows, then they went to some communist statues in the city and vandalized them. Of course, they made a proper film of the action which was all great when it was shared and lots of people liked the video, and for sure overnight they became a big name in the city. (It would also suggest not putting anything that can be taken as an illegal activity when promoting video.) The media took to it as well making it a huge story over the vandalization of the statues. Like always, the media put pressure on the police to get involved. The police came down hard and raided 15 guys' houses in the middle of the night. What was a promising club with already 50 guys was finished after just doing one action. Because the club had no time to build a good foundation and form a bond between members to put in proper leadership and plan B it was over as fast as it started. It is better to start small, with small actions to test the club's strength before taking on a bigger role. Focus on building a strong core before looking to grab a five-minute headline in some bugmans article.

In 2022, seeing a live stream full of angry analysis of a news article, empty threats, and super chat messages competing for most shocking to the ‚Äúnormies‚Äù feels stale. It feels like something out of its time. Worse than offensive, it now feels boring. Activists are craving action, and they are finding that the 3.0 lifestyle personified in the W2R brand is their roadmap on this path. In ever-increasing numbers, they are lacing up their sneakers and their gloves and starting the journey together. Perhaps the most interesting thing to note about this evolution of ‚ÄúExtreme‚Äù is that the new edge, the new radical, is actually far more serious than the dark fantasies of the terminally online WN 2.0. The leaked chats and dox articles of previous years reveal a fundamental disregard for the realities of the pro-White struggle. If one could freely talk about the violent overthrow of the system on the system‚Äôs own tech networks, why would it need to be overthrown? With careless disregard for operational security, the edgelords of the past handed the system the rope to hang them with. On the other hand, leaked chats from RAM published in various news sources revealed none of the strange things other groups seemed to find necessary. The quotes were focused on the business of martial arts training and activism. The members of RAM were exactly who they said they were, in private and in public. This indisputable fact forced the slandering media to paste unrelated quotes from the fed-infiltrated organization into articles about RAM to try to force a connection in the minds of the public. It was largely unsuccessful, as the continued success of follow-on projects like W2R clearly shows. The modern world is fast-paced, and the movement‚Äôs future is yet to be written. One thing is certain: the activists who define ‚ÄúExtreme‚Äù in this new era will not be repeating the same unserious outsider antics of past years. Those who mark the true cutting edge in 2022 and beyond are those that are training hard, networking with friends, and doing real-life activism. The future will not be on what you say but what you do.

Despite the explicit and extreme statements tied to such a group, they were allowed to continue to operate, churning out clickbait material for the media in their chats. The mystery of their continued existence was solved in August 2021, when Eric Striker of National-Justice.com exposed the leader of the group, Joshua Sutter, as a long-time paid FBI informant. Suddenly the rigged game became more clear to activists who had found themselves caught up in the edge posting competition. The sadism, the extreme imagery, the satanic cult LARP WN‚Äôs had come to think they would have to accept in order to help their own people had been a trap planted by the enemy. These revelations spurred the next evolution of the movement as confused activists searched within to try and remember what it actually meant to be pro-White. In searching for a reminder of why they first turned to White Nationalism, many activists looked to the example of one of the most successful and highly-regarded pro-White groups, the Rise Above Movement. From their appearance on the national scene in 2016, RAM had garnered widespread positive attention and interest by emphasizing martial arts training, strong friendship, and personal development as a way of life. Their slick, exciting videos showed an attractive modern style and became the standard for pro-White media. Their appeal obviously frightened some of the movement‚Äôs enemies, as the members of RAM found themselves the target of trumped-up federal charges, arrested and hounded through multiple countries on a flimsy pretext. The disparity in the system‚Äôs creation and support of Atomwaffen with their suppression of RAM has not gone unnoticed by activists taking stock of the scene in 2022. Shocking and empty threats and gruesome dialogue are the scripts the movement‚Äôs enemies wrote for it. Meanwhile, a group encouraging fitness, combat sports, building strong friendships, and a positive image had the full weight of the media and judicial system brought down on them. It is obvious in the minds of today‚Äôs activists who approach the system fears more. As the movement absorbed and reacted to this lesson, it‚Äôs worth noting that the finger-pointing and infighting that so often follows a learning experience hasn‚Äôt materialized. This hasn‚Äôt been an empty debate won on a live stream, it‚Äôs an organic evolution in response to hard facts. Many members of today‚Äôs movement were caught up in the edge posting competition of past years at one time like everyone else. Hindsight is always 20/20, and rehashing past mistakes becomes unnecessary once they are learned from. What is happening in this transition to White Nationalism 3.0, activism as a lifestyle is that the movement has picked itself up, dusted itself off, and found a clear new path forward together. With the lessons of the past in their pockets, today‚Äôs activists are beginning to define and show the world what WN 3.0 will look like. Led by the examples of RAM and the Active Clubs, young White people are training in martial arts and sparring with comrades. They‚Äôre coming together on feats of activism that challenge them as a team, and are finding that they possess courage, resourcefulness, and creativity beyond their own expectations. Today, the definition of ‚ÄúExtreme‚Äù has been fully reclaimed from a few bad actors talking big from the false safety of home. The viewer metrics and chat traffic around Will2Rise, the Active Clubs, Patriot Front, and many others show indisputably that the WN 3.0 approach to activism is resonating, and the broader movement is evolving accordingly. Rather than competing for super chat donations by trying to yell the loudest slurs, activists and would-be activists are showing their stuff by sparring, training, and hitting the streets to spread their message.

The fall of the edgelords and the new cutting edge The concept of the ‚Äúextreme‚Äù or the ‚Äúradical‚Äù has always held an irresistible appeal for young men. To be seen as being at the cutting edge, the tip of the spear is a great motivator for the competitive behavior of men in any group or endeavor. Among the military, missions undertaken by the Special Forces set the standard for extreme, and they are looked at with admiration and envy as a result. Music and fashion subcultures seek out the bleeding edge of society‚Äôs standards in order to attract young people. The pro-White movement is no different and young pro-White men compete to meet and exceed the definition of radical set by their peers. Today, that definition has changed drastically. And yesterday‚Äôs movement edgelords fall far short of the expectations for today‚Äôs extreme pro-White radicals. Like any movement, the pro-White sphere has undergone an evolution since its renewed rise under titles like Alt-Right and White Nationalism 2.0 circa 2015. In those early days, the movement was almost entirely online. Forum culture from places like Iron March and /pol/ set the standards for discourse and activity. Edgy humor was a source of fun and excitement and continued to set the tone as the movement shifted into the real world. Personalities emerged, attracted to the energy of this organic internet uprising. Podcasts and live streams espousing the views of WN 2.0 popped up left and right. Most of the people involved were sincere in their efforts and dedication to White unity, but the nature of internet broadcasting shaped their methods. The competition for viewers and chat donations meant that a broadcaster had to be a little more offensive, a little edgier than their competition. Private chats of some WN 2.0 organizations took their cues from the media they consumed and pushed even further, edgy jokes blurring with real opinions until the chat members themselves were confused on the difference. The pro-White message to the wider world became obscured, coming in second to the competition to say the wildest and most shocking things from behind the false safety of a screen. The movement‚Äôs enemies diligently followed this upward trend in edgy discourse, aided by paid infiltration, big tech chat log leaks and poor operational security. The craziest chats from groups like Atomwaffen Division were eagerly harvested for opposition material. Screenshots of the content of the group‚Äôs channels were plastered all over hit piece articles by ProPublica, the SPLC, and others. For a long time following the leaks, a quick google search on any innocuous pro-White term would bring up a slew of articles with Atomwaffen pictures, quotes, and gruesome propaganda featured prominently. Any mention of a WN 2.0 subject or event in those years was accompanied by quotes from the Atomwaffen chat celebrating murder or advocating rape. Add in a few scary pictures with skull masks and guns and you have a blend toxic enough to repulse even the readers sympathetic to the pro-White cause.
